WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:03.790
Great. Welcome everybody. It's my great pleasure to chair this

2
00:00:03.840 --> 00:00:07.200
session, this major symposium on targeting programmed cell death.

3
00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:10.220
We are really excited to have you all here.

4
00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.580
This is actually a really exciting time for this field, and we think that there's a

5
00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:18.480
lot of opportunities here going beyond just the

6
00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:22.460
initial forms of cell death that we've known about for a long time, such

7
00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:26.360
as apoptosis, but down the road, targeting other alternate forms of

8
00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:29.540
cell death, such as ferroptosis. And today, we're going to be talking a little bit

9
00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:31.020
about some of those opportunities.

10
00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:32.800
So we're glad to have you here.

11
00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:37.100
So I wanted to provide just a little bit of context before we get started.

12
00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:41.580
And as I've mentioned, there's several different forms of programmed

13
00:00:41.620 --> 00:00:45.240
cell death that have now been identified, including apoptosis, ferroptosis,

14
00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:49.180
necroptosis, pyroptosis. In fact, there's probably a new form of cell

15
00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:52.040
death described just about every month in the literature.

16
00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:57.140
And I think this opens up a lot of really exciting opportunities going forward

17
00:00:57.220 --> 00:01:00.720
to not only understand which forms of cell death are targetable

18
00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:05.060
and potentially can lead to more effective therapies for cancer

19
00:01:05.121 --> 00:01:08.680
patients, but also identifying where these forms of cell death

20
00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:11.400
actually interface. Where is the crosstalk between them?

21
00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:15.780
And how can we push cells from one form of cell death to another to

22
00:01:15.820 --> 00:01:19.300
potentially elicit anti-cancer immune responses or other

23
00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:21.200
more effective treatments?

24
00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:28.240
Importantly, when we talk about the time that it takes to actually

25
00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:31.980
target programmed cell death in the clinic, this can be a multi-decades

26
00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.180
endeavor. And I'm showing you here how long it's been since we've actually

27
00:01:36.220 --> 00:01:39.720
discovered that BCL2 has oncogenic properties.

28
00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:43.720
This was first done in 1988. All the way through, it took about 20

29
00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:46.960
years to come up with the first drugs targeting

30
00:01:47.020 --> 00:01:50.740
BCL2 that had clinical activity and were found to be

31
00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:51.220
safe.

32
00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:55.820
And that led to the 2016 FDA approval for

33
00:01:55.840 --> 00:01:59.130
venetoclax, ABT-199, which now has been

34
00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:03.240
utilized in scores of patients to be highly effective at

35
00:02:03.260 --> 00:02:06.200
controlling CLL, AML, and other heme malignancies.

36
00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:09.970
However, we are further behind with some of our other

37
00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:14.520
proteins that we're trying to target, especially in the BCL2 family.

38
00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:19.060
So here I'm showing you a quick overview of some of the key pro-survival proteins

39
00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:22.860
that we know are potentially targetable in apoptosis.

40
00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:27.290
So BCL2, we already have a drug, and actually several other additional drugs that

41
00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:30.520
have been FDA approved to target this protein.

42
00:02:30.560 --> 00:02:34.489
Extremely effective at controlling several different heme malignancies,

43
00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:38.300
including CLL, AML, few other hematologic malignancies.

44
00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:42.320
However, we are much further behind when it comes to targeting some of these other

45
00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.340
key pro-survival proteins, including BCLXL and MCL1,

46
00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:50.340
which have been hampered by some on-target and some poorly understood,

47
00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:54.160
in certain cases, toxicities. Interestingly, we are

48
00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:57.920
standing now at a time in the field where we are starting to understand those

49
00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:01.860
toxicities much more effectively and we're able to overwhelm or

50
00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:05.660
overcome them through some innovative drug engineering.

51
00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:08.220
And we'll hear about some of that here today.

52
00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:13.980
I wanted to just leave with a quick slide showing you what are the key

53
00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:17.700
areas of focus for this field of targeting apoptosis that will then

54
00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:21.420
apply also to the targeting of alternate cell death pathways in the

55
00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:21.840
future.

56
00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:26.700
So step one in this field was really developing selective potent

57
00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:28.660
inhibitors of pro-survival proteins.

58
00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:32.500
These are the anti-apoptotic proteins that cancer cells rely upon to

59
00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:34.329
survive. I feel like we've

60
00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:39.000
mostly completed that task. We have very good inhibitors of the major

61
00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:42.600
pro-survival proteins. We also have done a great job of

62
00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:45.760
identifying which cancers might be sensitive to single agent

63
00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:48.220
treatment with these inhibitors.

64
00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:52.940
Where we still are lacking is the remaining steps here, which includes

65
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.180
combination treatments that are able to

66
00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:59.580
leverage targeted therapies and other

67
00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:03.920
lineage-based vulnerabilities in combination with BH3 mimetics

68
00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:06.680
to drive enhanced cancer cell death.

69
00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:11.160
We also need to learn more about how we can potentially get the right

70
00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:14.900
drugs to the right patients. So even within a cancer type where we know that

71
00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:18.740
there's high BCL2 dependence in CLL, for example, how do we know which

72
00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:20.959
patients are going to respond most favorably?

73
00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:24.760
It's actually a big interest of our current NCI director, Anthony

74
00:04:24.780 --> 00:04:28.580
Letai, who's pioneered the use of BH3 profiling for that

75
00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:32.250
type of answer. We also need

76
00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:36.360
to help ensure that our pro-survival protein inhibitors, such as

77
00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:39.720
inhibitors of BCLXL and MCL1, are adequately tolerated.

78
00:04:39.740 --> 00:04:42.600
We know that there are some toxicities there, and we really need to understand them

79
00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:46.219
better and find clever ways to get around that.

80
00:04:46.230 --> 00:04:50.090
And finally, we need to understand where are the limitations,

81
00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:54.500
such as solid tumors. Targeting them with BH3 mimetics has

82
00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:57.960
been more difficult due to their inherent resistance to apoptotic cell

83
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.380
death. How do we potentially overcome that?

84
00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:05.360
And also in heme malignancies, as we'll hear today from Andreas and also

85
00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:09.340
from Larry Boyse, there's high rates of development of

86
00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:10.980
resistance to some of these agents.

87
00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:14.780
And so we need to better understand what are those modes of resistance development

88
00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:18.420
and how we can also evade those. So with that, I'm very

89
00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:22.280
excited to turn over the podium to our first speaker, Andreas Strasser from the

90
00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:26.090
Walter and Eliza Hall Institute. He'll be telling us about enhancing the activity

91
00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:28.700
of BH3 mimetics. Let's welcome him to the podium.

92
00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:36.460
Thank you very much, Chris. Thank you very much

93
00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:38.480
to everyone for coming.

94
00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:44.620
So here's my disclosures. I'd like you to

95
00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:48.260
note them, especially the first two or three.

96
00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:53.520
As Chris already introduced, this is the apoptotic

97
00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:57.600
pathway as we know it today. The cell death pathway that is probably best

98
00:05:57.660 --> 00:05:58.140
studied,

99
00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:02.440
and it's regulated or executed by the

100
00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:06.292
pro-apoptotic proteins Bax and Bak.In healthy cells,

101
00:06:06.372 --> 00:06:09.692
these proteins are kept in check by the pro-survival proteins like

102
00:06:09.952 --> 00:06:12.252
BCL2 and MCL1, BCLXL.

103
00:06:13.712 --> 00:06:17.652
And cells commit to death when the BH3-only proteins

104
00:06:17.712 --> 00:06:21.302
are increased in response to stresses such as chemotherapeutic

105
00:06:21.372 --> 00:06:21.732
drugs.

106
00:06:22.572 --> 00:06:26.412
This happens through transcriptional or post-transcriptional processes.

107
00:06:27.092 --> 00:06:30.972
The BH3-only proteins bind with very high affinity to the pro-survival

108
00:06:30.992 --> 00:06:34.552
proteins, and that liberates Bax and Bak to kill the cells.

109
00:06:35.392 --> 00:06:39.332
Some BH3-only proteins have also been reported to be able to activate

110
00:06:39.372 --> 00:06:40.952
Bax and Bak directly.

111
00:06:42.092 --> 00:06:45.512
Because of the knowledge of this pathway, as Chris mentioned,

112
00:06:46.172 --> 00:06:50.112
BH3 mimetic drugs have been developed with

113
00:06:50.152 --> 00:06:53.912
the BCL2 inhibitor venetoclax, the one that is approved and

114
00:06:54.012 --> 00:06:55.752
used regularly in the clinic.

115
00:06:58.352 --> 00:07:02.192
The challenge with BH3 mimetic drugs, as

116
00:07:02.252 --> 00:07:06.172
we see it come for all of them, and certainly is already the case for venetoclax,

117
00:07:06.472 --> 00:07:09.851
is emergence of resistance to BCL2

118
00:07:09.892 --> 00:07:12.962
inhibition. This shows the survival of CLL

119
00:07:13.252 --> 00:07:16.952
patients, as published by Andrew Roberts from our institute

120
00:07:17.152 --> 00:07:18.352
a few years ago.

121
00:07:20.032 --> 00:07:20.412
So

122
00:07:21.592 --> 00:07:25.012
our groups at WEHI and many groups around the world have been

123
00:07:25.112 --> 00:07:28.892
studying mechanisms of resistance by studying patients,

124
00:07:29.072 --> 00:07:32.672
or we have done CRISPR gene knockout and gene activation

125
00:07:32.812 --> 00:07:35.232
screens in cells. And

126
00:07:36.252 --> 00:07:40.092
what came up was, to me, the most surprising thing was point

127
00:07:40.152 --> 00:07:44.022
mutations in BCL2. I would have predicted any mutation in

128
00:07:44.032 --> 00:07:47.582
BCL2 that affects binding of venetoclax will also

129
00:07:47.582 --> 00:07:51.512
abrogate its binding of the BH3-only proteins and therefore make it a null

130
00:07:51.552 --> 00:07:52.362
protein. Well,

131
00:07:53.312 --> 00:07:55.292
nature is different than what I think.

132
00:07:56.282 --> 00:08:00.252
Upregulation of the untargeted proteins was seen very regularly in

133
00:08:00.352 --> 00:08:04.092
our CRISPR gene activation screens and also in

134
00:08:04.132 --> 00:08:08.102
resistant samples in patients. Loss of Bax we found as

135
00:08:08.212 --> 00:08:11.932
a top hit in our genetic screens. It's also been

136
00:08:12.012 --> 00:08:14.511
seen not very frequently in patients.

137
00:08:15.451 --> 00:08:19.241
The biggest surprise for us was our biggest hit in our genetic screens and

138
00:08:19.272 --> 00:08:22.492
knockouts was p53. And

139
00:08:23.432 --> 00:08:26.292
we thought, "Well, that makes no sense at all." The BH3

140
00:08:27.232 --> 00:08:30.792
mimetics were made in part precisely because they work

141
00:08:30.872 --> 00:08:34.293
downstream of p53. p53 is one of the

142
00:08:34.312 --> 00:08:37.982
transcriptional activators of the BH3-only proteins like Bim and

143
00:08:38.092 --> 00:08:41.492
Puma and Noxa. So how can a mutation in

144
00:08:41.732 --> 00:08:44.322
p53 affect this pathway?

145
00:08:45.832 --> 00:08:49.712
And we were really puzzled, but then pretty much at that

146
00:08:49.772 --> 00:08:52.132
time when we got these genetic screen data,

147
00:08:53.192 --> 00:08:57.092
these data came out from patient cohorts, and that is

148
00:08:57.592 --> 00:09:01.072
loss of p53 in CLL portends poorer survival,

149
00:09:01.712 --> 00:09:04.832
and in AML, mutations in p53 portend

150
00:09:05.312 --> 00:09:09.212
absolutely dismal prognosis. So that meant

151
00:09:09.272 --> 00:09:13.232
what we found in the lab probably does matter, and we should find out

152
00:09:13.812 --> 00:09:17.752
how p53 influences the response to BH3

153
00:09:17.772 --> 00:09:18.612
mimetic drugs.

154
00:09:20.172 --> 00:09:24.012
Sarah Diepstra, a postdoc with Jemah Kelly, then did

155
00:09:24.592 --> 00:09:28.372
an experiment that I told her you should never do because it's entirely stupid,

156
00:09:29.492 --> 00:09:33.252
and that was to look whether when you treat cells with a BH3

157
00:09:33.292 --> 00:09:37.192
mimetic drug, in this case, these are our workhorse Miklin lymphoma

158
00:09:37.232 --> 00:09:40.652
lines, which are highly dependent on MCL1, so she treated with an

159
00:09:40.752 --> 00:09:44.252
MCL1 inhibitor, but she's seen the same in BCL2

160
00:09:44.312 --> 00:09:47.112
sensitive cells with venetoclax treatment.

161
00:09:47.512 --> 00:09:51.492
There is an increase in p53 protein, suggesting that

162
00:09:51.532 --> 00:09:54.392
maybe p53 becomes activated.

163
00:09:55.812 --> 00:09:59.252
And as I said before, this is also seen in human

164
00:09:59.292 --> 00:10:01.772
lymphoma cells, not just in mouse lymphomas.

165
00:10:03.112 --> 00:10:06.272
Not only is p53 stabilized and therefore

166
00:10:06.532 --> 00:10:10.442
putatively activated, it is actually activated because when

167
00:10:10.472 --> 00:10:14.262
we did RNA-seq analysis of BH3 mimetic

168
00:10:14.352 --> 00:10:18.152
drug-treated lymphoma cells, one of the top pathways that was

169
00:10:18.192 --> 00:10:21.892
upregulated is the p53 signaling pathway.

170
00:10:22.732 --> 00:10:26.012
And here is just an example of some of the classical

171
00:10:26.112 --> 00:10:29.992
p53 target genes that are clearly activated in these

172
00:10:30.032 --> 00:10:33.832
lymphoma cells when they're treated with an IC50 or

173
00:10:33.952 --> 00:10:37.832
IC75 or IC90 of this MCL1

174
00:10:37.872 --> 00:10:41.672
inhibitor. Noxa, Puma, Bim, p21, all these

175
00:10:41.732 --> 00:10:44.912
classical target genes are highly upregulated.

176
00:10:46.872 --> 00:10:47.512
So

177
00:10:48.572 --> 00:10:51.112
that then made us wonder whether

178
00:10:52.212 --> 00:10:55.752
perhaps when mitochondrial outer membrane

179
00:10:55.872 --> 00:10:59.652
permeabilization is induced, maybe sufficiently to

180
00:10:59.672 --> 00:11:03.332
kill the cells or maybe even more importantly, kind of on the

181
00:11:03.352 --> 00:11:07.132
borderline when some cells might actually be able to survive that

182
00:11:07.172 --> 00:11:07.652
treatment,

183
00:11:08.962 --> 00:11:12.072
mOMP somehow leads to p53 activation,

184
00:11:12.272 --> 00:11:15.862
perhaps through release of mitochondrial DNA, a

185
00:11:15.892 --> 00:11:19.532
process that was studied by Ben Kyle many years ago, who's

186
00:11:19.772 --> 00:11:20.652
sitting over there.

187
00:11:22.172 --> 00:11:26.032
Indeed, that was the case because when Sarah made Bax/Bak

188
00:11:26.092 --> 00:11:29.872
double knockout variant of these lymphoma cells, which are

189
00:11:29.912 --> 00:11:33.652
shown on the right here, when these cells are treated with the MCL1

190
00:11:33.692 --> 00:11:36.812
inhibitor, there's no more increase in p53.

191
00:11:38.012 --> 00:11:38.512
Oops.

192
00:11:39.412 --> 00:11:39.872
And

193
00:11:40.912 --> 00:11:44.792
this is not because p53 cannot be activated in these cells, because when

194
00:11:44.812 --> 00:11:48.252
they're treated with the MDM2 inhibitor nutlin, p53

195
00:11:48.272 --> 00:11:50.592
levels go up dramatically.

196
00:11:51.452 --> 00:11:52.112
And also,

197
00:11:53.192 --> 00:11:55.372
the removal of Bax and Bak actually

198
00:11:56.212 --> 00:12:00.092
completely abolished the induction of Puma, Noxa,

199
00:12:00.532 --> 00:12:03.932
and Bim after treatment with a BH3 mimetic drug.

200
00:12:04.012 --> 00:12:04.992
So this

201
00:12:06.112 --> 00:12:08.472
process is clearly dependent on

202
00:12:08.732 --> 00:12:12.628
mOMP.So

203
00:12:12.708 --> 00:12:13.188
this is

204
00:12:14.108 --> 00:12:17.848
our hypothesis that we then had, and that is that p53 may

205
00:12:17.888 --> 00:12:21.248
function not only as an inducer of apoptosis by

206
00:12:21.348 --> 00:12:24.848
transcriptional induction of the proapoptotic BH3-only genes,

207
00:12:25.408 --> 00:12:29.208
but that's also as an enforcer. So perhaps in

208
00:12:29.288 --> 00:12:33.088
cells that are kind of off the brink of whether they die or will not die,

209
00:12:34.008 --> 00:12:35.648
MAMP, through release of

210
00:12:36.888 --> 00:12:40.768
mitochondrial DNA, can then activate p53

211
00:12:40.828 --> 00:12:44.448
in a way to amplify apoptosis signaling to get more

212
00:12:44.468 --> 00:12:48.088
p53 activity. Exactly how MAMP activates

213
00:12:48.128 --> 00:12:50.228
p53, we haven't actually worked out.

214
00:12:52.488 --> 00:12:56.218
In leukemia cells that would be p53 deficient or

215
00:12:56.308 --> 00:13:00.088
mutant, this amplification loop will not happen,

216
00:13:00.708 --> 00:13:04.608
so some tumor cells may survive, and that may be the seed for

217
00:13:04.648 --> 00:13:07.868
disease relapse that is seen in venetoclax plus

218
00:13:07.908 --> 00:13:11.848
azacitidine-treated AML or in venetoclax plus

219
00:13:11.908 --> 00:13:13.628
a CD20 antibody-treated

220
00:13:15.128 --> 00:13:15.628
CLL.

221
00:13:18.548 --> 00:13:22.508
So one thing that we also noted when we were doing these

222
00:13:22.548 --> 00:13:23.968
experiments is that

223
00:13:25.148 --> 00:13:28.238
the induction of BIM, NOXA, and

224
00:13:28.328 --> 00:13:32.208
PUMA was actually reduced by knocking out p53, but

225
00:13:32.268 --> 00:13:36.248
it wasn't absolutely abrogated. There was still a way to

226
00:13:36.308 --> 00:13:39.768
upregulate it. And we thought this could be very interesting.

227
00:13:39.828 --> 00:13:43.728
We would like to know what the mechanism of that is, and if we understand

228
00:13:43.768 --> 00:13:47.608
that mechanism, then maybe if that could be activated

229
00:13:47.648 --> 00:13:51.488
pharmacologically, then this could be a way to boost

230
00:13:51.688 --> 00:13:54.728
the effects of BH3 mimetic drugs in the clinic.

231
00:13:56.128 --> 00:13:56.368
So the

232
00:13:57.548 --> 00:14:00.808
RNA-seq analysis that I showed you the data already actually

233
00:14:00.888 --> 00:14:04.368
provided an excellent clue to what the mechanism was.

234
00:14:04.848 --> 00:14:05.708
So the top hit

235
00:14:06.788 --> 00:14:09.688
in the RNA-seq was not actually the p53 pathway.

236
00:14:09.748 --> 00:14:12.768
The top hit was interferon alpha response,

237
00:14:13.468 --> 00:14:16.948
and that immediately made us think of cGAS-STING

238
00:14:17.068 --> 00:14:20.848
signaling. So this pathway is activated

239
00:14:21.008 --> 00:14:24.528
in response to cytosolic DNA, for example, viral

240
00:14:24.568 --> 00:14:28.328
DNA or mitochondrially released DNA, as

241
00:14:29.048 --> 00:14:32.868
discovered by Flavell and Ben Kyle and their groups many years ago.

242
00:14:33.588 --> 00:14:37.288
This leads to the activation of STING, which then activates

243
00:14:37.368 --> 00:14:40.088
TBK1. TBK1 can activate

244
00:14:40.648 --> 00:14:44.568
IRF3. And quite interestingly, it was

245
00:14:44.628 --> 00:14:48.168
already shown that IRF3 may be able to activate

246
00:14:48.188 --> 00:14:51.968
transcription of BIM. So we thought, well, maybe this is

247
00:14:52.048 --> 00:14:54.168
actually the pathway we should be studying.

248
00:14:55.308 --> 00:14:58.708
Indeed, in these lymphoma cells and many other

249
00:14:58.748 --> 00:15:02.048
leukemia and lymphoma cells of mouse and human origin,

250
00:15:02.708 --> 00:15:06.128
when we treat them with BH3 mimetic drugs, STING is

251
00:15:06.208 --> 00:15:09.668
activated, TBK1 is activated, IRF3

252
00:15:10.288 --> 00:15:13.328
is activated. And this is entirely

253
00:15:13.388 --> 00:15:17.068
independent of p53 because it's still seen in the

254
00:15:17.108 --> 00:15:20.448
p53 knockout derivatives of these lymphoma cells.

255
00:15:21.808 --> 00:15:25.648
And correspondingly to that, when you knockout

256
00:15:31.288 --> 00:15:31.628
STING,

257
00:15:32.968 --> 00:15:36.488
these cells, when they're treated with an MCL-1 inhibitor, there's less

258
00:15:36.508 --> 00:15:40.408
induction of NOXA or PUMA and BIM. It's not abrogated

259
00:15:40.888 --> 00:15:44.728
similarly to what we saw with the p53 knockout in the same lymphoma

260
00:15:44.908 --> 00:15:48.268
cells. Of note, when you do a double knockout of

261
00:15:48.308 --> 00:15:51.918
p53 and STING, their induction is almost entirely

262
00:15:52.008 --> 00:15:55.508
abrogated, indicating that it's really these two

263
00:15:55.668 --> 00:15:59.248
pathways that drive this feed-forward loop, one

264
00:15:59.348 --> 00:16:02.968
activation of p53, the other one activation of the

265
00:16:03.008 --> 00:16:04.868
cGAS-STING pathway.

266
00:16:07.168 --> 00:16:10.788
So with these data in hand, we thought, well, maybe we could actually

267
00:16:10.808 --> 00:16:12.988
exploit this knowledge. Maybe

268
00:16:13.828 --> 00:16:15.268
if we combine

269
00:16:16.108 --> 00:16:19.888
STING agonists with a BH3 mimetic drug, maybe we'll get much more

270
00:16:19.908 --> 00:16:22.608
bang for our buck than with either agent

271
00:16:23.128 --> 00:16:27.028
alone, with the hope that maybe this would also

272
00:16:27.068 --> 00:16:31.008
be possible then to use with BH3 mimetic drugs that at the

273
00:16:31.068 --> 00:16:34.868
moment, as Chris mentioned, are progressing relatively slowly in the clinic

274
00:16:35.268 --> 00:16:37.088
because of their on-target toxicity.

275
00:16:37.168 --> 00:16:39.888
Maybe this will allow us to reduce their

276
00:16:40.388 --> 00:16:41.408
concentrations.

277
00:16:42.348 --> 00:16:45.528
So this is the STING agonist that we worked with.

278
00:16:47.058 --> 00:16:48.788
They are all highly potent.

279
00:16:49.628 --> 00:16:51.528
STING agonists were originally

280
00:16:52.948 --> 00:16:56.888
developed by several pharma companies, not with the aim to

281
00:16:56.908 --> 00:17:00.748
induce apoptosis in an intrinsic manner in cells as

282
00:17:00.828 --> 00:17:03.648
we discovered, but actually by

283
00:17:04.348 --> 00:17:07.969
stimulating the immune system, hoping that this would further

284
00:17:07.988 --> 00:17:09.168
boost the immune

285
00:17:10.189 --> 00:17:13.949
activation effects of PD-1 or PD-L1 or CDL4

286
00:17:14.748 --> 00:17:18.689
inhibitors. The good news about the work that was done on these STING

287
00:17:18.748 --> 00:17:21.748
agonists is that they are safe in patients.

288
00:17:22.508 --> 00:17:26.459
The bad news is that in boosting cancer immunotherapy,

289
00:17:27.248 --> 00:17:29.608
the signal hasn't been very strong.

290
00:17:31.348 --> 00:17:35.148
So first thing we did is to see whether STING agonists on their own

291
00:17:35.228 --> 00:17:38.848
can actually kill leukemia and lymphoma cells, and

292
00:17:38.908 --> 00:17:42.788
indeed they can. So this is a group of MCL lymphoma

293
00:17:42.828 --> 00:17:46.468
cells. This is the levels of STING that is found in these cells.

294
00:17:46.488 --> 00:17:48.788
It's not super high, but it's present.

295
00:17:49.368 --> 00:17:53.228
And very interestingly, the potency of the STING agonist is

296
00:17:53.248 --> 00:17:56.988
directly correlated to the amount of STING found in these lymphoma

297
00:17:57.028 --> 00:18:00.188
cells. So this cell here that has relatively little

298
00:18:00.228 --> 00:18:04.048
STING is the most resistant. This that has the most is the most

299
00:18:04.128 --> 00:18:07.028
sensitive one. Knockout of p53

300
00:18:07.748 --> 00:18:11.428
provides some protection, but not far from complete

301
00:18:11.468 --> 00:18:15.380
protection.We then

302
00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:18.540
did the control experiment to show that the STING

303
00:18:18.600 --> 00:18:22.000
agonists, as they're supposed to do, they activate

304
00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:25.980
TBK1, they activate IRF3, and

305
00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:30.020
this activation is entirely independent of

306
00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:33.780
p53. It doesn't require MOMP either, because a

307
00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:37.860
Bax-Bak double knockout cell, the STING agonist still activates

308
00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:41.900
IRF3, still induces massive levels of BIM,

309
00:18:42.420 --> 00:18:44.439
and also substantial levels of Puma.

310
00:18:44.510 --> 00:18:48.480
The antibodies to PumaHCH is not very good, so that's why the signal is

311
00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:49.300
not that strong.

312
00:18:50.820 --> 00:18:54.360
The killing of these lymphoma cells, as you would predict, is entirely

313
00:18:54.370 --> 00:18:58.320
dependent on IRF3, because when Sarah knocked

314
00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:02.040
out IRF3, the killing of these cells was pretty

315
00:19:02.080 --> 00:19:03.180
much abrogated.

316
00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:08.580
So that means the pathway that is engaged by the STING agonist

317
00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:12.420
is STING activating TBK1 and IRF3,

318
00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:14.860
and that induces Noxa, Puma, and BIM.

319
00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:17.360
The NF-kappaB activation pathway,

320
00:19:18.220 --> 00:19:21.940
I haven't shown you the data, but is not required for cell killing.

321
00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:28.700
The next thing that Sarah did is to see whether the killing of

322
00:19:29.120 --> 00:19:32.940
cells by STING agonists is entirely apoptosis

323
00:19:33.060 --> 00:19:35.860
or whether other cell death pathways may also play a role.

324
00:19:36.420 --> 00:19:40.260
It is entirely apoptosis because Bax-Bak double knockout cells

325
00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:44.280
are entirely resistant to STING agonist treatment, and the

326
00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:47.890
killing is actually pretty much accounted for by the transcriptional

327
00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:51.690
induction of Noxa, Puma, and BIM, because these triple knockouts

328
00:19:52.180 --> 00:19:55.340
are almost as resistant as the Bax-Bak double knockouts.

329
00:19:55.420 --> 00:19:59.280
Maybe there's another BH3-only protein that plays a role as well.

330
00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:06.280
The next thing that we did is to check whether the

331
00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:10.140
STING agonists can actually boost the killing of lymphoma and

332
00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:14.060
leukemia cells induced by BH3 mimetic drugs,

333
00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:18.080
and indeed it can. So this is the killing you get with

334
00:20:18.220 --> 00:20:22.100
an MCL-1 inhibitor. This is the killing you get with

335
00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:25.660
a STING agonist, and this is the killing that you get in the

336
00:20:25.700 --> 00:20:26.980
combination treatment.

337
00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:31.920
This is entirely unaffected by p53 knockout, and

338
00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:35.920
it's entirely apoptotic cell death because the Bax-Bak double knockout cells are

339
00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:38.960
completely resistant to that killing.

340
00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:42.880
So the next step was to go in

341
00:20:43.940 --> 00:20:47.860
vivo and see whether the STING agonists can

342
00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:50.160
provide a protective effect. So

343
00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:54.960
this is experiments-- The first experiments we did was in Rag

344
00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.920
knockout mice, because our lymphoma cells have Cas9

345
00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:00.660
in them, which is highly immunogenic.

346
00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:04.160
So if you put them into a wild-type mouse, they just get immune

347
00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:04.840
rejected.

348
00:21:06.560 --> 00:21:10.160
So this is the protective effect you get with the STING

349
00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:13.580
agonist. This is the protective effect you get with the

350
00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:17.100
MCL-1 inhibitor, and you get a much greater protection.

351
00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:20.780
About 50% of mice actually survive with the dual treatment.

352
00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:25.980
If the cancer cells are p53 knockout,

353
00:21:26.540 --> 00:21:30.509
there's still a high protective effect of the dual treatment, but it

354
00:21:30.580 --> 00:21:34.560
is diminished. Now, please remember that curve here.

355
00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:38.400
So this is the survival that we see in immune deficient

356
00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:40.040
mice, in Rag knockout mice.

357
00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:42.760
The next experiment that Sarah did

358
00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:46.960
was to actually do it in mice with a competent immune system.

359
00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:50.860
So for that, we just took Cas9 transgenic mice, which are

360
00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:54.880
immunologically tolerant to Cas9, so the lymphoma cells don't

361
00:21:54.920 --> 00:21:56.740
get rejected by the immune system.

362
00:21:57.320 --> 00:21:59.060
And what you can see here is that

363
00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:03.880
even when the lymphoma cells are knockout for p53, the STING

364
00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:07.400
agonist alone gives phenomenal extension of

365
00:22:07.460 --> 00:22:11.370
lifespan. So a mouse with a MIC lymphoma that lives at 100 days

366
00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:14.890
will live at 300 days. They're essentially cured,

367
00:22:15.720 --> 00:22:19.540
and the combination with the BH3 mimetic drug gave even greater

368
00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:20.180
protection.

369
00:22:22.520 --> 00:22:24.220
So moving on from that,

370
00:22:25.300 --> 00:22:29.100
we were wondering which other hematological cancers or

371
00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:32.720
solid cancers could be candidates for such a

372
00:22:32.780 --> 00:22:34.579
combination treatment. So

373
00:22:35.579 --> 00:22:36.199
these are

374
00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:40.460
looking at published data, RNA-seq published data sets.

375
00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:44.900
And when you look at acute myeloid leukemia, they have very high

376
00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:48.360
levels of STING. This is the levels of STING across

377
00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:52.420
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Some subtypes have very high levels of

378
00:22:52.440 --> 00:22:55.560
STING, but many actually are very, very low.

379
00:22:55.700 --> 00:22:57.300
So a lot of

380
00:22:58.280 --> 00:23:02.260
B-cell lymphomas in humans, for example, are actually quite low

381
00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:06.040
for STING or don't have detectable STING levels, so you'd

382
00:23:06.080 --> 00:23:08.700
predict they would not respond to a STING agonist.

383
00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:14.120
So this is in vitro experiments with AML patient samples.

384
00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:18.800
The red ones are from p53 mutant relapsed

385
00:23:18.900 --> 00:23:22.520
AML. And when they're treated with the STING agonist,

386
00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:26.800
all of them are potently killed with the exception of this one.

387
00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:30.560
And in most of these AML samples in vitro,

388
00:23:31.340 --> 00:23:34.540
the combination of venetoclax plus the STING agonist gives

389
00:23:35.260 --> 00:23:38.720
substantially more killing than either agent alone.

390
00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:42.400
So the final data that I'll show you is this one here.

391
00:23:42.480 --> 00:23:45.940
So this is an experiment with a human AML

392
00:23:46.060 --> 00:23:48.540
PDX in NSG-SGG3 mice.

393
00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:53.060
And the single agent treatment with a STING agonist

394
00:23:53.140 --> 00:23:57.120
gives very marked protection. Combining it-- and this

395
00:23:57.200 --> 00:24:00.090
is a venetoclax-resistant disease, adding

396
00:24:00.100 --> 00:24:03.320
venetoclax adds some survival advantage.

397
00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:07.080
But most importantly, when you look at the leukemic burden

398
00:24:07.320 --> 00:24:11.100
by intramedullary biopsy, there's another one and a half

399
00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:15.060
log drop in leukemic cells in the dual combination of

400
00:24:15.100 --> 00:24:17.060
venetoclax plus the

401
00:24:17.900 --> 00:24:20.240
STING agonist compared to the STING agonist

402
00:24:20.760 --> 00:24:24.060
alone.So in summary,

403
00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:28.460
we believe that p53 not only triggers cell death

404
00:24:28.940 --> 00:24:32.160
by apoptosis, but it can also enforce it through this

405
00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:33.360
amplification loop.

406
00:24:34.190 --> 00:24:37.800
We also believe that STING agonists can induce proapoptotic

407
00:24:37.840 --> 00:24:41.500
BH3-only proteins transcriptionally, and this is in a

408
00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:45.380
p53-independent manner, but IRF-3-dependent

409
00:24:45.440 --> 00:24:45.740
manner.

410
00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:46.880
And

411
00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:51.180
we believe that this tumor cell intrinsic effect of the STING

412
00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:55.020
agonists can actually be further boosted when the

413
00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:57.900
immune system in a human patient is competent,

414
00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:02.180
presumably by activating tumor-specific T cells,

415
00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:04.120
getting more bang for the buck.

416
00:25:05.100 --> 00:25:08.840
And our hope is that combining BH3 mimetic drugs with STING

417
00:25:08.900 --> 00:25:12.219
agonists may be going forward into

418
00:25:12.600 --> 00:25:14.260
clinical assessments. And

419
00:25:15.360 --> 00:25:15.880
indeed,

420
00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:20.620
there is a clinical trial that is being ramped up in Melbourne,

421
00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.980
run by Andrew Wei and Andrew Roberts, across many

422
00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:28.440
centers, including the Royal Melbourne Hospital, Peter Mac,

423
00:25:28.580 --> 00:25:30.500
the O&amp;J, and

424
00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:31.920
it's

425
00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:34.320
just recruiting at the moment.

426
00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:39.960
Our research questions is how can we increase STING expression in cancer

427
00:25:39.980 --> 00:25:43.960
cells that actually have very low levels of STING,

428
00:25:44.020 --> 00:25:47.800
and we have made quite a bit of advance on that, and we think that

429
00:25:47.860 --> 00:25:48.900
could be quite interesting.

430
00:25:50.140 --> 00:25:54.040
And finally, we believe that the STING pathway may be

431
00:25:54.100 --> 00:25:57.820
just only one pathway to boost the expression of BIM,

432
00:25:57.920 --> 00:26:01.660
PUMA, and other BH3-only proteins, which could be harnessed to

433
00:26:01.700 --> 00:26:05.080
get more bang for buck out of BH3 mimetic drugs.

434
00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:09.300
And we have done and are doing this by having made transcriptional

435
00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:13.080
reporters for BIM and PUMA, and we've done

436
00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:16.340
CRISPR knockout and CRISPR gene activation screens.

437
00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:20.340
And, in fact, one of our hits was STING, which was really

438
00:26:20.380 --> 00:26:24.040
gratifying. But we have new hits that we're really interested in

439
00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:25.160
working with. So,

440
00:26:26.480 --> 00:26:27.340
I'd like to thank

441
00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:32.400
Sulios, with whom we've done this work with the STING agonists, and this

442
00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:36.320
work was run by Gemma Kelly, who I work

443
00:26:36.360 --> 00:26:39.960
very closely with, by Sarah, and by Eddie

444
00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.940
Lamarkat. And I'm very happy to answer questions.

445
00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:44.020
Thank you very much.

446
00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:54.520
If there are questions, please come up to the microphones. David.

447
00:26:54.560 --> 00:26:55.800
Hi, Andreas. Great talk.

