00:35:04.636 --> 00:35:08.586
well as our team. I'm going to talk not about lymphoma or

595
00:35:08.616 --> 00:35:11.796
leukemia, as Andreas did. I'm going to talk mostly about, actually all about

596
00:35:11.856 --> 00:35:13.036
multiple myeloma here,

597
00:35:14.156 --> 00:35:16.996
and thinking about some of the questions that we've been asking.

598
00:35:17.056 --> 00:35:19.366
And so our myeloma team's been very important for this,

599
00:35:20.316 --> 00:35:21.316
and other collaborators

600
00:35:22.156 --> 00:35:23.986
across the continent,

601
00:35:24.996 --> 00:35:27.536
and actually into Europe, too, now that I look at the list.

602
00:35:27.596 --> 00:35:30.926
Our funding, and of course, we use a lot of patient samples for this work, and so I

603
00:35:30.956 --> 00:35:34.256
want to thank our patients and their families as well to get started.

604
00:35:36.576 --> 00:35:36.916
And so

605
00:35:37.816 --> 00:35:41.716
about really 20 years ago, we started thinking about myeloma as

606
00:35:41.756 --> 00:35:45.436
maybe a little bit of a different disease in the fact that the drugs we were

607
00:35:45.556 --> 00:35:49.496
using for them were targeting things that are found in every cell, like

608
00:35:49.536 --> 00:35:53.486
proteasome inhibitors. So it suggested there were functional dependencies

609
00:35:53.496 --> 00:35:57.456
in myeloma that may not be related to what was actually driving the disease.

610
00:35:57.496 --> 00:36:01.326
And we were able to finally show this after almost

611
00:36:01.496 --> 00:36:05.176
20 years in a collaboration with Constantine Mitsiades at the Dana-Farber

612
00:36:05.216 --> 00:36:07.696
Cancer Institute, where we looked at

613
00:36:08.636 --> 00:36:12.576
using the DepMap data, preferential dependencies in myeloma,

614
00:36:12.616 --> 00:36:14.986
a plasma cell malignancy of the bone marrow,

615
00:36:16.576 --> 00:36:20.196
that weren't found in any other of the types of cells in the DepMap

616
00:36:20.256 --> 00:36:23.746
database. And we found 116 of these genes.

617
00:36:24.446 --> 00:36:26.712
And I guess what was remarkable about...

618
00:36:26.852 --> 00:36:30.332
about those 116 genes was that none of them were actually

619
00:36:30.712 --> 00:36:34.652
oncogenes. If you go back into these cells, or if you actually look into large

620
00:36:34.752 --> 00:36:38.732
data sets of which we did that had mutation and

621
00:36:38.752 --> 00:36:42.592
gene expression data on 1,000 newly diagnosed myeloma patients, you just don't see

622
00:36:42.672 --> 00:36:46.132
mutations in these genes. A gain of them

623
00:36:46.292 --> 00:36:50.032
or activating type or mutations.

624
00:36:50.432 --> 00:36:53.862
So what do you see? And this talks a little bit about what the

625
00:36:54.292 --> 00:36:57.942
types of genes these are. So a lot of them are transcriptional regulators,

626
00:36:57.972 --> 00:37:01.932
and many of them are actually essential transcription factors for plasma

627
00:37:01.992 --> 00:37:02.632
cell

628
00:37:04.512 --> 00:37:05.612
differentiation and

629
00:37:06.452 --> 00:37:10.072
maintenance. You see a lot shown here in green of things

630
00:37:10.112 --> 00:37:13.892
associated with protein folding because these are antibody-secreting cells, and so

631
00:37:13.952 --> 00:37:17.312
if you muck up that, the cells do not tolerate it, and that's probably why

632
00:37:17.322 --> 00:37:20.412
proteasome inhibitors, or at least these cells are very sensitive to proteasome

633
00:37:20.472 --> 00:37:24.012
inhibitors. And there's other things in here that are also consistent with cell of

634
00:37:24.072 --> 00:37:27.692
origin plasma cell phenotypes. And one of those included

635
00:37:28.112 --> 00:37:30.352
mitochondrial regulators of apoptosis.

636
00:37:30.392 --> 00:37:33.052
And so we've been actually looking at all of these

637
00:37:33.992 --> 00:37:35.312
areas over the last

638
00:37:36.472 --> 00:37:39.992
decade or so. But I'm really just going to focus on that last one about regulation

639
00:37:40.032 --> 00:37:43.932
of cell death. And one of the early studies that we had done

640
00:37:43.972 --> 00:37:47.132
on this was with Brian Gaudette, a former graduate student.

641
00:37:47.582 --> 00:37:51.192
And he just took data from normal plasma cells,

642
00:37:52.152 --> 00:37:55.492
gene expression data from normal plasma cells, from myeloma plasma cells, or from

643
00:37:55.532 --> 00:37:59.482
another plasma cell dyscrasia called Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia, and

644
00:37:59.552 --> 00:38:02.942
asked what are the differences in expression of the BCL2 families, and these are

645
00:38:02.992 --> 00:38:06.942
using these old data sets. And the only one that he actually found that was

646
00:38:06.972 --> 00:38:09.532
really different between normal plasma cells

647
00:38:10.392 --> 00:38:13.812
in light blue and myeloma cells in dark blue was

648
00:38:13.832 --> 00:38:17.052
BCL2L11. And you should all know what this is now because

649
00:38:18.112 --> 00:38:20.012
Andreas was talking about that a lot.

650
00:38:20.052 --> 00:38:23.942
It's the gene that encodes BIM. And that seems a little bit

651
00:38:24.012 --> 00:38:27.952
backwards to think of a cell acquiring resistance to

652
00:38:27.972 --> 00:38:31.892
cell death, and the one gene we see upregulated is a pro-apoptotic gene.

653
00:38:32.272 --> 00:38:36.012
But it really is consistent with why cells have to evade cell death because

654
00:38:36.052 --> 00:38:39.952
oncogenic stress actually is pro-apoptotic, and we've known

655
00:38:40.012 --> 00:38:42.992
that for some time. And what that results in is this

656
00:38:43.932 --> 00:38:46.372
concept of mitochondrial priming, such that

657
00:38:47.252 --> 00:38:51.072
anti-apoptotic proteins like Mcl1, Bcl-x, and BCL2

658
00:38:51.152 --> 00:38:55.092
have to sequester these pro-apoptotic proteins that are being made due to

659
00:38:55.132 --> 00:38:58.892
the chronic oncogenic stress the cell goes through during the

660
00:38:58.932 --> 00:39:02.052
transformation process for that cell to live, and that's what they have to evade

661
00:39:02.092 --> 00:39:05.032
it. But that actually comes with a consequence.

662
00:39:05.052 --> 00:39:09.002
And now it tends to lower the apoptotic threshold so that if you give another

663
00:39:09.052 --> 00:39:09.401
signal

664
00:39:10.632 --> 00:39:14.372
such as therapy, it can activate the BH3 proteins as Andreas

665
00:39:14.392 --> 00:39:17.832
discussed which could cause the release of BIM and

666
00:39:17.892 --> 00:39:20.852
activate BAX and BAK and cause cytochrome C release.

667
00:39:21.252 --> 00:39:25.152
Where in normal cells, we just don't have that level of mitochondrial priming or in

668
00:39:25.232 --> 00:39:28.852
drug-resistant cells, and you don't get the cytochrome C release.

669
00:39:29.772 --> 00:39:30.152
And so

670
00:39:31.112 --> 00:39:35.012
we've been studying this for some time, but even not only we were, but

671
00:39:35.232 --> 00:39:38.812
actually Chris was, and when he was a postdoc, he did this beautiful study, which I

672
00:39:38.852 --> 00:39:40.032
hope he's not showing in his talk.

673
00:39:40.952 --> 00:39:44.852
Good. And that looking in myeloma and showed that

674
00:39:44.892 --> 00:39:48.692
the level of priming correlated in patients with the

675
00:39:48.712 --> 00:39:52.692
response to therapy shown here, and it didn't matter what the therapy

676
00:39:52.792 --> 00:39:55.552
was. The more priming you had, the more likely the patient was

677
00:39:56.432 --> 00:39:59.792
going to respond, and the outcomes were better in the patients

678
00:39:59.852 --> 00:40:02.432
that had a higher overall priming.

679
00:40:02.961 --> 00:40:06.252
And so we've really spent a lot of our time thinking about

680
00:40:06.672 --> 00:40:10.392
how does this work. And one of the things we found was

681
00:40:10.412 --> 00:40:14.052
that in patient samples, in cell lines, and

682
00:40:14.092 --> 00:40:15.072
everything we were looking at,

683
00:40:15.912 --> 00:40:19.212
nearly all myelomas were Mcl1 dependent.

684
00:40:20.372 --> 00:40:22.092
And we see that.

685
00:40:23.132 --> 00:40:26.032
We do see that we get also

686
00:40:27.052 --> 00:40:28.912
what I'll call BCL2 agonists here.

687
00:40:28.942 --> 00:40:32.272
They can be BH3 mimetics, or they could be PROTACs.

688
00:40:32.872 --> 00:40:36.472
That some cells, while Mcl1 dependent, are also

689
00:40:36.752 --> 00:40:40.522
codependent on BCL2 or Bcl-x, and we can use those things in

690
00:40:40.612 --> 00:40:44.552
combination. However, sometimes we see that BCL2 and Bcl-x are

691
00:40:44.591 --> 00:40:45.432
there and

692
00:40:46.252 --> 00:40:47.211
bound to BIM.

693
00:40:48.172 --> 00:40:52.132
But when you release them, you don't kill the cell because all the BIM moves

694
00:40:52.232 --> 00:40:54.912
over to free Mcl1. That gets

695
00:40:57.832 --> 00:41:01.212
stabilized by that binding. And so what I'm going to go

696
00:41:01.312 --> 00:41:05.252
through really for the rest of the talk is examples of how

697
00:41:06.932 --> 00:41:10.152
both extrinsic signals, which could be therapy, kind of

698
00:41:10.932 --> 00:41:13.232
similar to what Andreas was talking about.

699
00:41:13.262 --> 00:41:17.212
They could be from the microenvironment, or there could be intrinsic

700
00:41:17.312 --> 00:41:21.092
signals within the cell, such as oncogene activation, and how

701
00:41:21.492 --> 00:41:25.132
that influences this priming. And so we'll start with therapy.

702
00:41:25.172 --> 00:41:29.072
And what Shannon Matulis in the lab did was she took

703
00:41:29.392 --> 00:41:33.152
cells that were resistant to venetoclax here, and I'll show you why

704
00:41:33.312 --> 00:41:35.972
we call these resistant. Even this one is highly resistant with that

705
00:41:36.592 --> 00:41:37.312
micromolar

706
00:41:38.172 --> 00:41:38.532
killing

707
00:41:39.792 --> 00:41:40.122
curves.

708
00:41:41.052 --> 00:41:44.972
And she asked, "Well, what happens?" Well, she already knew from work that Alejo

709
00:41:45.012 --> 00:41:47.462
Morales had done earlier in the lab that most of these, the reason why they don't

710
00:41:47.472 --> 00:41:51.212
respond to venetoclax is there's no BIM or anything else on BCL2 in those

711
00:41:51.252 --> 00:41:55.192
cells, and so they don't respond. But one of them was a curious one to

712
00:41:55.272 --> 00:41:59.192
us, which was this red one, KMS18, because as you can see in

713
00:41:59.212 --> 00:42:03.192
this Co-IP, there's lots of BIM

714
00:42:03.252 --> 00:42:05.772
bound to BCL2. It's actually where most of it's found.

715
00:42:06.332 --> 00:42:09.472
But as I showed in the cartoon on the earlier slide, when we added venetoclax to

716
00:42:09.512 --> 00:42:13.252
these cells, all of it moves to Mcl1, and the

717
00:42:13.292 --> 00:42:16.562
cells are resistant. And I'll just point out that with this,

718
00:42:16.652 --> 00:42:20.352
Mcl1 proteins go up. This is a protein stability issue,

719
00:42:20.432 --> 00:42:24.392
not a transcriptional effect. And that becomes important later

720
00:42:24.412 --> 00:42:28.252
when we think about some of the types of oncogenic effects that occur during

721
00:42:28.292 --> 00:42:32.032
multiple myelomaSo Shannon wanted to

722
00:42:32.052 --> 00:42:35.452
find what were drugs that could actually increase the priming on these cells, and

723
00:42:35.492 --> 00:42:39.312
she turned to one that we use an awful lot in myeloma is Dexamethasone.

724
00:42:39.352 --> 00:42:43.332
And she found that, and this is just quantitating into two lines what

725
00:42:43.452 --> 00:42:43.732
happens

726
00:42:45.052 --> 00:42:46.271
in the IP level

727
00:42:48.012 --> 00:42:51.532
to the levels of BIM. So you can see Dex increases total BIM and increases the

728
00:42:51.552 --> 00:42:55.112
priming on cells or binding of BIM to Mcl1,

729
00:42:55.152 --> 00:42:57.692
Bcl2, Bcl-x. It doesn't really change the pattern very much.

730
00:42:58.132 --> 00:43:01.472
Venetoclax clearly changes the pattern in both of these because you're releasing

731
00:43:02.032 --> 00:43:05.732
things, and picked up by Mcl1. But the combination of them, you

732
00:43:05.752 --> 00:43:09.692
completely end up releasing enough BIM from Bcl2 such that

733
00:43:10.172 --> 00:43:13.392
you kill the cells. And we show in patient samples that, in fact, this can have

734
00:43:13.412 --> 00:43:16.992
profound effects when you add Dexamethasone, such that all of these resistant

735
00:43:17.572 --> 00:43:21.312
cells, some of these tumors become highly sensitive.

736
00:43:21.732 --> 00:43:25.632
And in fact, Jonathan Koffman translated this to a clinical trial

737
00:43:25.752 --> 00:43:29.732
adding Dexamethasone to Venetoclax in the very early phase one and phase

738
00:43:29.832 --> 00:43:33.432
two, and increased the overall response rates that were seen there.

739
00:43:34.502 --> 00:43:38.372
Another factor that we looked at was stromal components.

740
00:43:38.392 --> 00:43:42.232
And so what Shannon Matulas did in this experiment was she took

741
00:43:42.452 --> 00:43:46.232
myeloma cells that were isolated from patients, and she either did

742
00:43:46.532 --> 00:43:50.172
purified plasma cells or she used them with the

743
00:43:50.212 --> 00:43:53.382
stroma that came out of the bone marrow aspirate, and then treated them with

744
00:43:53.412 --> 00:43:57.372
ABT-737, the Bcl2, Bcl-x inhibitor that Chris

745
00:43:57.392 --> 00:43:59.652
mentioned in his introduction talk.

746
00:43:59.672 --> 00:44:02.732
And in every case, if there was stroma there, the cells became much more resistant

747
00:44:03.452 --> 00:44:07.422
to the drug. And so she then modeled this in cell lines and took

748
00:44:07.452 --> 00:44:11.212
a cell line and showed that, in fact, if you culture cells, co-culture with a

749
00:44:11.252 --> 00:44:15.232
stromal component or condition media from those cells, you made the

750
00:44:15.252 --> 00:44:17.172
