00:48:00.332 --> 00:48:03.682
found in myeloma. And so we decided to focus on that

814
00:48:04.072 --> 00:48:06.142
initially. And so we made knock-in

815
00:48:07.032 --> 00:48:10.332
mutations of either an alanine or glutamic acid.

816
00:48:10.492 --> 00:48:13.672
And with Venetoclax, we didn't really see anything particularly interesting.

817
00:48:14.292 --> 00:48:18.062
And these are in the cells that-- This was actually JP Dougherty

818
00:48:18.152 --> 00:48:19.962
doing. These are the cells where there was

819
00:48:20.892 --> 00:48:24.792
high phosphorylation. And interestingly enough, when you make the alanine mutant,

820
00:48:24.832 --> 00:48:26.012
you do make the cells more

821
00:48:27.172 --> 00:48:30.252
resistant to the Mcl1 inhibitor

822
00:48:30.312 --> 00:48:34.048
AZD5991.Becca focused on the cell that

823
00:48:34.128 --> 00:48:38.008
didn't have phosphorylation, and she did BH3 profiling, which I

824
00:48:38.028 --> 00:48:41.688
know that Chris will talk more about in his

825
00:48:41.748 --> 00:48:45.368
talk. And so using peptides that bind

826
00:48:45.448 --> 00:48:49.368
promiscuously to the different BCL2 proteins, we

827
00:48:49.448 --> 00:48:51.088
really didn't see any change in priming.

828
00:48:51.628 --> 00:48:55.048
But the one place we did see it was this HRK peptide.

