1039
01:00:11.624 --> 01:00:14.924
trials. No drop in ejection fraction, no catastrophic

1040
01:00:15.624 --> 01:00:19.544
congestive heart failure. So that happens when you do it

1041
01:00:19.584 --> 01:00:23.464
in a mouse. You do a complete knockout of Mcl1, which is

1042
01:00:23.584 --> 01:00:26.804
different from inhibiting Mcl1, and then you get cardiac failure.

1043
01:00:26.844 --> 01:00:29.864
But in patients, to my knowledge, was never been observed.

1044
01:00:29.924 --> 01:00:31.184
I just want to make that clear.

1045
01:00:31.664 --> 01:00:34.314
No, I think that's correct with all of them.

1046
01:00:34.364 --> 01:00:37.184
But I think what was being observed was you were seeing

1047
01:00:38.744 --> 01:00:41.404
proteins in the blood that were spiking and going up.

1048
01:00:41.484 --> 01:00:45.240
So while they had not become-Then I had a clinical event

1049
01:00:45.480 --> 01:00:49.040
that was clearly evidence of cardiotoxicity based on

1050
01:00:49.480 --> 01:00:52.260
release of cardioprotections measured in the blood.

1051
01:00:53.200 --> 01:00:56.640
So this spike in these "cardiac proteins"

1052
01:00:57.520 --> 01:00:58.000
comes from the

1053
01:00:58.800 --> 01:01:02.420
spleen. So when you have massive lysis of leukemic cells,

1054
01:01:02.900 --> 01:01:03.080
the

1055
01:01:04.680 --> 01:01:08.500
kidney is secreting this.

1056
01:01:09.140 --> 01:01:12.000
And so it's not necessarily cardiac.

1057
01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:15.260
But clinically, again, there was never any cardiac.

1058
01:01:16.340 --> 01:01:20.300
But I think it scared the companies enough to just stop it because of the history

1059
01:01:20.460 --> 01:01:24.380
of the genetics that Joe Offerman had showed years earlier to

1060
01:01:24.420 --> 01:01:25.450
say that it would be there.

1061
01:01:29.460 --> 01:01:31.040
May I ask a question?

1062
01:01:31.300 --> 01:01:31.360
Yes.

1063
01:01:31.680 --> 01:01:32.860
A really nice talk.

1064
01:01:34.260 --> 01:01:38.200
I have a really general question regarding BCL2 biology, and whether,

1065
01:01:38.880 --> 01:01:41.260
have you ever tested integrated stresses

1066
01:01:42.140 --> 01:01:44.140
have played a role in the BCL2

1067
01:01:45.740 --> 01:01:46.660
protein stability?

1068
01:01:47.640 --> 01:01:48.060
I'm sorry, which?

1069
01:01:48.620 --> 01:01:51.440
The integrated stresses condition.

1070
01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:54.300
Yeah, such as ER stress, something like that.

1071
01:01:54.310 --> 01:01:57.980
Yeah. So, those pathways can induce things like Noxa

1072
01:01:58.540 --> 01:01:58.880
and

1073
01:02:00.600 --> 01:02:04.520
I think Puma, and I think Bim also gets induced by that as

1074
01:02:04.620 --> 01:02:07.300
well. So those pathways definitely induce that.

1075
01:02:07.760 --> 01:02:11.500
In the case of Noxa, Noxa can recruit one of the E3

1076
01:02:11.540 --> 01:02:14.860
ligases there. And in fact, the reason why Bim probably

1077
01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:18.740
stabilizes MCL1, in fact, and the MCL1 inhibitors stabilize

1078
01:02:19.140 --> 01:02:23.060
MCL1, is you end up blocking the ability to recruit

1079
01:02:23.080 --> 01:02:24.100
the E3 ligase

1080
01:02:24.940 --> 01:02:26.480
through that Noxa protein.

1081
01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:27.660
Okay. Thank you.

1082
01:02:28.960 --> 01:02:30.500
Yeah. Great. Let's thank Larry.

1083
01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:37.040
Okay, great.

1084
01:02:37.840 --> 01:02:41.480
Well, I'm very honored to have the final talk of today's

1085
01:02:41.540 --> 01:02:45.500
session. We're going to change our focus a little bit from heme malignancies

1086
01:02:45.540 --> 01:02:49.420
to solid tumors, and I'm going to take you through a couple of stories about how

1087
01:02:49.460 --> 01:02:52.980
we believe we can potentially enhance therapy

1088
01:02:53.060 --> 01:02:56.640
outcomes for solid tumors by targeting the same apoptosis pathway.

1089
01:02:57.500 --> 01:02:58.580
These are my disclosures.

1090
01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:03.080
So a lot of what I'll show you today has to do with ovarian

1091
01:03:03.120 --> 01:03:06.760
cancer, but it's actually broadly applicable to a wide range of different

1092
01:03:06.800 --> 01:03:10.700
solid cancers. And I'll really show you at the very end data across a

1093
01:03:10.760 --> 01:03:14.640
wide variety of solid cancer cell lines and other models

1094
01:03:14.680 --> 01:03:18.220
that we've used to then validate some of the things that I'll show you here.

1095
01:03:18.240 --> 01:03:20.840
But I will focus on ovarian cancer. It's actually a fascinating disease.

1096
01:03:21.260 --> 01:03:24.980
Typically diagnosed at an advanced stage, high disease

1097
01:03:25.080 --> 01:03:27.800
burden. Pretty poor outcomes overall.

1098
01:03:28.200 --> 01:03:31.880
About 20% of patients are cured with the cytotoxic chemotherapy that we

1099
01:03:31.920 --> 01:03:34.810
administer, with 80% of patients relapsing.

1100
01:03:35.640 --> 01:03:39.260
The period of treatment response is quite variable from patient to

1101
01:03:39.360 --> 01:03:43.200
patient. But typically, with every stage of treatment,

1102
01:03:43.260 --> 01:03:47.160
there's less and less period of response, and a

1103
01:03:47.260 --> 01:03:48.920
less likelihood of potential cure.

1104
01:03:49.500 --> 01:03:51.760
So what do we actually treat ovarian cancer with?

1105
01:03:51.860 --> 01:03:55.620
Well, it's cytotoxic drugs, paclitaxel and carboplatin.

1106
01:03:55.680 --> 01:03:59.360
So carboplatin is a DNA-damaging alkylating agent, and

1107
01:03:59.420 --> 01:04:02.100
paclitaxel is a microtubule hyperstabilizer.

1108
01:04:02.520 --> 01:04:06.420
Now these drugs, platinum agents and paclitaxel, are widely used in other

1109
01:04:06.540 --> 01:04:10.440
solid cancers, which we think is part of the reason why some of

1110
01:04:10.480 --> 01:04:13.620
the things that I'm going to show you are actually applicable to other solid

1111
01:04:13.630 --> 01:04:17.100
tumors. Importantly, both of these therapies are known to

1112
01:04:17.120 --> 01:04:20.480
produce high levels of proapoptotic signals in cancer

1113
01:04:20.500 --> 01:04:24.469
cells. So whether the cells are going to die or not via the apoptosis

1114
01:04:24.500 --> 01:04:28.200
pathway is a side question, but we do know that we are producing a lot of

1115
01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:31.480
apoptotic signaling in response to these treatments.

1116
01:04:32.780 --> 01:04:36.620
So we wanted to know whether potentially enhancing the ability for those

1117
01:04:36.680 --> 01:04:40.320
apoptotic signals to actually trigger apoptotic cell death could be

1118
01:04:40.440 --> 01:04:43.960
an interesting and efficacious treatment for ovarian

1119
01:04:44.060 --> 01:04:47.900
cancer and other solid tumors. Now, our lab uses a lot of BH3

1120
01:04:47.920 --> 01:04:48.430
profiling.

1121
01:04:49.260 --> 01:04:53.200
Larry already introduced this assay to some extent, and I won't go into the

1122
01:04:53.300 --> 01:04:57.140
details of it. It was actually something developed by the current NCI director,

1123
01:04:57.300 --> 01:05:00.849
Tony Letai. But the basic premise is that we're taking cells and

1124
01:05:00.880 --> 01:05:04.640
exposing their mitochondria to proapoptotic signals in the form of these

1125
01:05:04.659 --> 01:05:08.600
BH3 peptides. And they mimic the activity of proapoptotic

1126
01:05:08.609 --> 01:05:11.800
proteins such as Bim and Bid. We've talked about those here today.

1127
01:05:12.280 --> 01:05:15.860
And so we're essentially able to titrate in death doses and then

1128
01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:19.460
determine or watch for the release of cytochrome C from

1129
01:05:19.500 --> 01:05:23.240
mitochondria, which shows that the cells have committed themselves to apoptotic

1130
01:05:23.320 --> 01:05:27.000
cell death. That allows us to measure something called apoptotic priming, or

1131
01:05:27.040 --> 01:05:30.600
the cell's proximity to the apoptotic threshold, which we found

1132
01:05:30.640 --> 01:05:34.300
multiple times is really important for how cells are going to respond to different

1133
01:05:34.360 --> 01:05:35.580
types of therapies.

1134
01:05:36.940 --> 01:05:39.700
We also can use this assay to do something a little bit different, which is to

1135
01:05:39.760 --> 01:05:41.420
measure apoptotic dependencies.

1136
01:05:41.740 --> 01:05:45.540
So these are cellular dependencies on pro-survival proteins, such as the ones that

1137
01:05:45.560 --> 01:05:48.760
have been described today. And we do this by using

1138
01:05:48.780 --> 01:05:52.270
BH3 peptides derived from other proteins such as

1139
01:05:52.280 --> 01:05:55.700
Bad, HRK, Ms1 or MCL1,

1140
01:05:56.600 --> 01:05:59.730
Noxa. And this allows us to not only

1141
01:05:59.780 --> 01:06:00.920
identify

1142
01:06:01.860 --> 01:06:05.850
how primed cells are, but actually what proteins we need to target in order

1143
01:06:05.880 --> 01:06:08.840
to drive cell death or drive apoptosis in those cells.

1144
01:06:08.850 --> 01:06:12.740
And that's important because we actually now have developed BH3 mimetics

1145
01:06:12.780 --> 01:06:15.760
that target many of these proteins, and they're available clinically.

1146
01:06:16.180 --> 01:06:17.320
So I've shown a few here.

1147
01:06:18.600 --> 01:06:22.140
ABT-199, venetoclax, is a very potent BCL2 inhibitor,

1148
01:06:22.780 --> 01:06:26.700
FDA approved for use in CLL and AML and a few

1149
01:06:26.740 --> 01:06:29.980
other heme malignancies. But we also have ones that are targeting

1150
01:06:30.060 --> 01:06:34.000
BCL-XL, including navitoclax that targets BCL2 and BCL-XL.

1151
01:06:34.260 --> 01:06:38.020
This was actually the first BCL2/BCL-XL inhibitor to make it to the clinic.

1152
01:06:38.400 --> 01:06:41.880
Unfortunately, also causes that thrombocytopenia that we've talked about that would

1153
01:06:41.920 --> 01:06:45.236
be part of the focus of today's talk.We also have

1154
01:06:45.876 --> 01:06:49.176
very specific MCL-1 inhibitors such as S63845.

1155
01:06:49.236 --> 01:06:52.936
This is a drug made by Servier. A very, very good MCL-1 inhibitor,

1156
01:06:53.316 --> 01:06:57.056
does have some of these cardiac troponin signals that Larry was just talking about.

1157
01:06:57.576 --> 01:07:00.856
So it's been slow going clinically with those agents.

1158
01:07:01.396 --> 01:07:04.976
And then finally, we have drugs that target BCL-XL specifically, which is really

1159
01:07:04.996 --> 01:07:06.696
going to be the focus of what I'm going to talk about.

1160
01:07:07.276 --> 01:07:11.196
And these include the original drug, WEHI539, but then also

1161
01:07:11.396 --> 01:07:14.336
next generation inhibitors that are very potent, like

1162
01:07:14.376 --> 01:07:18.216
A-1331852, and then a BCL-XL

1163
01:07:18.236 --> 01:07:21.876
PROTAC degrader DT2216, which we find to be a very

1164
01:07:21.936 --> 01:07:25.716
effective, very exciting molecule that is now in clinical trials.

1165
01:07:27.116 --> 01:07:30.985
So we use BH3 profiling to look for these dependencies, and

1166
01:07:31.016 --> 01:07:34.596
then translate those or then test and validate those with some of these

1167
01:07:34.616 --> 01:07:36.896
BH3 medics that we know have clinical relevance.

1168
01:07:37.936 --> 01:07:41.776
So in ovarian cancer specifically, we first started out with just a very

1169
01:07:41.816 --> 01:07:45.686
basic study using high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma cell lines,

1170
01:07:46.036 --> 01:07:49.586
and we tested their overall apoptotic priming with this BH3 profiling

1171
01:07:49.676 --> 01:07:53.556
assay. And what we found is uniformly across these cell lines, they did

1172
01:07:53.596 --> 01:07:57.456
respond to these proapoptotic signals with release of cytochrome C,

1173
01:07:57.516 --> 01:08:01.216
indicating that the apoptosis pathway is alive and well in these ovarian cancer

1174
01:08:01.336 --> 01:08:04.916
cell lines. We also tested their sensitivity to

1175
01:08:04.936 --> 01:08:08.176
BCL-XL specific or MCL-1 specific or

1176
01:08:08.276 --> 01:08:09.336
BCL-2

1177
01:08:10.176 --> 01:08:13.836
dependent-- tested for the dependencies on those pro-survival proteins.

1178
01:08:14.166 --> 01:08:17.896
And the most consistent thing we found was that they do express or do

1179
01:08:17.936 --> 01:08:21.757
exhibit BCL-XL dependence, as indicated by the response to the

1180
01:08:21.916 --> 01:08:23.106
HRK peptide here.

1181
01:08:24.596 --> 01:08:28.356
They did not show much sensitivity to the MCL-1 inhibition,

1182
01:08:28.677 --> 01:08:32.616
and I'll show you in a subsequent slide that this is also not reflecting any

1183
01:08:32.677 --> 01:08:36.496
BCL-2 inhibition or dependence. We took a step back and also

1184
01:08:36.536 --> 01:08:39.677
looked at DepMap data to look at expression of BCL-2

1185
01:08:40.436 --> 01:08:42.096
family proteins as well as dependencies.

1186
01:08:42.536 --> 01:08:46.066
We see that in ovarian cancer, there's actually extremely low levels of

1187
01:08:46.076 --> 01:08:49.596
BCL-2. And we've talked a lot about BCL-2 because it's a very relevant

1188
01:08:49.616 --> 01:08:52.156
protein for targeting of heme malignancies.

1189
01:08:52.177 --> 01:08:54.536
It turns out in solid cancers, it's kind of hit or miss.

1190
01:08:54.576 --> 01:08:56.677
It's expressed in some but not others.

1191
01:08:56.706 --> 01:09:00.596
And in ovarian cancer, one of the reasons that BCL-XL turns out to be such a great

1192
01:09:00.656 --> 01:09:02.876
target is because BCL-2 is very low.

1193
01:09:02.986 --> 01:09:06.036
So you don't have to deal with this additional pro-survival protein that's

1194
01:09:06.056 --> 01:09:10.016
buffering against cell death. We see that BCL-XL encoded by

1195
01:09:10.056 --> 01:09:13.996
BCL2L1 is very highly expressed in ovarian cancer cell lines, and

1196
01:09:14.056 --> 01:09:18.036
MCL-1 is highly expressed as well with lower levels of BCL-W.

1197
01:09:19.076 --> 01:09:22.996
When we actually knock these out via CRISPR or in the

1198
01:09:23.036 --> 01:09:26.637
DepMap database, when these are knocked out via CRISPR, we see that really only

1199
01:09:26.656 --> 01:09:30.436
BCL-XL is a pretty uniformly

1200
01:09:30.496 --> 01:09:33.316
essential gene in these ovarian cancer cell lines.

1201
01:09:33.346 --> 01:09:34.766
This is 50 some cell lines,

1202
01:09:35.576 --> 01:09:39.106
indicating that this is probably the strongest of all the pro-survival proteins in

1203
01:09:39.156 --> 01:09:42.656
ovarian cancers. There's some mild dependence on MCL-1 seen here.

1204
01:09:44.177 --> 01:09:47.956
However, when we actually treat these cells with BCL-XL inhibitors

1205
01:09:47.996 --> 01:09:48.496
or

1206
01:09:49.496 --> 01:09:50.996
MCL-1 inhibitors, we see that there

1207
01:09:52.137 --> 01:09:55.276
is some degree of apoptosis induced, but it's fairly mild.

1208
01:09:55.956 --> 01:09:56.336
And that's

1209
01:09:57.556 --> 01:10:01.036
due to the fact that these cells actually undergo pretty rapid apoptotic

1210
01:10:01.136 --> 01:10:04.826
adaptation, where they're upregulating other pro-survival proteins to help them

1211
01:10:04.936 --> 01:10:08.896
survive. And so we knew that we had to actually combine the BCL-XL

1212
01:10:08.936 --> 01:10:12.096
inhibition with other agents in order to then fully

1213
01:10:12.156 --> 01:10:14.616
drive significant amounts of cell death.

1214
01:10:15.496 --> 01:10:19.216
So utilizing our panel of high-grade serous ovarian

1215
01:10:19.236 --> 01:10:22.766
carcinoma cell lines, we combined BCL-XL inhibitors or

1216
01:10:22.876 --> 01:10:26.136
BCL-2 or MCL-1 inhibitors with standard of care agents.

1217
01:10:26.156 --> 01:10:29.876
And what I'm showing you here is just the responses to the agents alone on the

1218
01:10:29.916 --> 01:10:32.456
left versus in combination with paclitaxel.

1219
01:10:32.926 --> 01:10:36.536
And paclitaxel was synergistic in the vast majority of these

1220
01:10:36.896 --> 01:10:39.196
high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma cell lines.

1221
01:10:40.716 --> 01:10:43.476
We saw this was also true when we looked at colony formation assays.

1222
01:10:43.526 --> 01:10:47.496
Anytime we inhibit BCL-XL in combination with paclitaxel, we

1223
01:10:47.556 --> 01:10:51.436
see very potent induction of cell death and elimination of

1224
01:10:51.496 --> 01:10:55.096
colony outgrowth. This was not true at all for BCL-2 inhibition or

1225
01:10:55.176 --> 01:10:58.826
MCL-1. And interestingly, when we inhibit BCL-XL and

1226
01:10:58.876 --> 01:11:02.315
MCL-1 together, we eradicate the colonies

1227
01:11:02.356 --> 01:11:02.956
completely,

1228
01:11:03.796 --> 01:11:06.606
and that's irrespective of whether the paclitaxel is actually there or not,

1229
01:11:06.716 --> 01:11:10.636
indicating that the co-targeting of MCL-1 and BCL-XL is going to be the

1230
01:11:10.696 --> 01:11:12.796
most effective way forward.

1231
01:11:13.716 --> 01:11:17.196
When we looked at actually patient specimens, we wanted to see whether there was

1232
01:11:17.276 --> 01:11:20.836
also indications of potential BCL-XL or other types of dependence

1233
01:11:20.896 --> 01:11:22.916
in high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma.

1234
01:11:23.426 --> 01:11:27.276
And interestingly, we did see that regardless of whether the patient

1235
01:11:27.356 --> 01:11:27.936
specimens were

1236
01:11:28.856 --> 01:11:32.416
from patients that were treatment naive or those that had received prior therapy

1237
01:11:32.816 --> 01:11:36.776
or neoadjuvant, we did see indications of BCL-XL dependence in these

1238
01:11:37.096 --> 01:11:40.575
patient tumors, indicating that this is not something restricted to just cell

1239
01:11:40.616 --> 01:11:40.916
lines.

1240
01:11:42.276 --> 01:11:45.896
Now, the targeting of BCL-XL for ovarian cancer therapy isn't a totally new idea.

1241
01:11:45.936 --> 01:11:47.636
This has been around for quite a few years.

1242
01:11:48.076 --> 01:11:51.836
But as we've been talking about throughout this session, there

1243
01:11:51.916 --> 01:11:55.676
is an on-target toxicity that we've had to kind of be

1244
01:11:55.756 --> 01:11:59.636
challenged with over the years, and that's the on-target thrombocytopenia caused by

1245
01:11:59.656 --> 01:12:03.056
BCL-XL inhibitors. As it turns out, platelets express

1246
01:12:03.256 --> 01:12:05.116
BCL-XL and are highly dependent on it.

1247
01:12:05.176 --> 01:12:08.836
So as soon as you dose animals or humans with

1248
01:12:08.936 --> 01:12:12.756
BCL-XL inhibitors, you see this very rapid platelet drop even within just a

1249
01:12:12.816 --> 01:12:13.576
few hours.

1250
01:12:14.376 --> 01:12:16.916
So we needed to come up with a way to overcome this.

1251
01:12:17.476 --> 01:12:21.396
In one side project, we actually looked at BCL-XL dependence in

1252
01:12:21.416 --> 01:12:25.056
human platelets and found that there's actually a difference between

1253
01:12:25.076 --> 01:12:28.176
platelets that are newly formed versus those that have been in circulation for

1254
01:12:28.216 --> 01:12:31.296
quite some time. We see that young platelets actually exhibit

1255
01:12:31.416 --> 01:12:35.376
lower level of apoptotic priming and also lower dependence

1256
01:12:35.436 --> 01:12:39.136
on BCL-XL. We took advantage of this in a mouse

1257
01:12:39.216 --> 01:12:41.796
model by treating mice with romiplostim, Nplate.

1258
01:12:41.816 --> 01:12:45.696
It's a thrombopoietin agonist, stimulating platelet production, and then

1259
01:12:45.756 --> 01:12:48.896
challenging the mice with navitoclax, that conventional BCL-XL

1260
01:12:48.936 --> 01:12:52.536
inhibitorWe saw that although we definitely still

1261
01:12:52.576 --> 01:12:56.496
induced apoptosis in a wide range of these platelets, the

1262
01:12:56.576 --> 01:12:59.696
platelet levels never reached those levels that would be considered to be below

1263
01:12:59.736 --> 01:13:03.576
normal in this mouse model, indicating that this may also be an effective

1264
01:13:03.656 --> 01:13:07.196
strategy for potentially protecting platelets or protecting patients from

1265
01:13:07.416 --> 01:13:09.216
BCL-XL-induced thrombocytopenia.

1266
01:13:10.616 --> 01:13:14.586
However, another strategy was developed by a collaborator of ours,

1267
01:13:14.656 --> 01:13:18.336
Dao-Hong Zhao, who came up with a really interesting idea to make

1268
01:13:18.396 --> 01:13:22.276
ABT-263 navitoclax into a PROTAC degrader

1269
01:13:22.316 --> 01:13:24.276
of BCL-XL instead of an inhibitor.

1270
01:13:24.636 --> 01:13:28.596
And that was done by taking the ABT-263 drug and linking it to an

1271
01:13:28.676 --> 01:13:32.096
E3 ligase ligand. So this would essentially trigger the

1272
01:13:32.136 --> 01:13:34.956
degradation of BCL-XL instead of its just simple

1273
01:13:34.996 --> 01:13:38.896
inhibition. This was very effective at degrading

1274
01:13:38.916 --> 01:13:42.756
BCL-XL in nucleated cells, but interestingly, platelets express very

1275
01:13:42.796 --> 01:13:46.666
low levels of VHL, and so they don't degrade BCL-XL in the same manner

1276
01:13:46.796 --> 01:13:49.396
and are actually largely protected from this agent.

1277
01:13:50.876 --> 01:13:54.576
In our hands, when we treat ovarian cancer cells with this degrader, we

1278
01:13:54.636 --> 01:13:57.876
see a very impressive potent downregulation of

1279
01:13:57.896 --> 01:14:01.516
BCL-XL. Within a few hours, we already start to see the

1280
01:14:01.536 --> 01:14:05.216
protein levels of this BCL-XL dwindling, and it's almost

1281
01:14:05.236 --> 01:14:08.366
completely gone across every cell line we've tested by 24 hours.

1282
01:14:10.036 --> 01:14:12.596
When we combine this with paclitaxel, we see something kind of interesting

1283
01:14:12.676 --> 01:14:16.176
happening, which is that the degrader consistently leads to

1284
01:14:16.476 --> 01:14:20.196
loss of BCL-XL across all of our models tested, shown here.

1285
01:14:20.596 --> 01:14:22.416
This is even just a low level of the degrader.

1286
01:14:23.116 --> 01:14:26.426
But when we combine this with paclitaxel, we see that paclitaxel leads to a

1287
01:14:26.456 --> 01:14:30.176
decrease in MCL1 levels. Across every cell line that we've

1288
01:14:30.216 --> 01:14:34.016
tested, for the vast majority of the cell lines tested, we see

1289
01:14:34.076 --> 01:14:36.536
this degradation of MCL1 occurring.

1290
01:14:36.586 --> 01:14:40.376
And then in the combination treatment, we see essentially the elimination of both

1291
01:14:40.396 --> 01:14:44.046
BCL-XL and MCL1, which we think is then driving this

1292
01:14:44.056 --> 01:14:46.936
synergistic apoptosis in those cells.

1293
01:14:47.676 --> 01:14:49.276
We wanted to look at this a little bit more formally.

1294
01:14:49.436 --> 01:14:51.236
So we utilized

1295
01:14:53.116 --> 01:14:56.496
a strategy to separate out the mitotically arrested versus

1296
01:14:56.536 --> 01:15:00.415
non-mitotically arrested cells in response to paclitaxel and then performed

1297
01:15:00.456 --> 01:15:04.336
BH3 profiling. We found that those that were arrested in

1298
01:15:04.356 --> 01:15:08.006
mitosis by paclitaxel treatment had a massive spike in their

1299
01:15:08.036 --> 01:15:11.836
apoptotic priming and also had a large increase in their

1300
01:15:11.856 --> 01:15:13.196
BCL-XL dependence.

1301
01:15:14.356 --> 01:15:17.656
Molecularly, what was happening in these cells is that those that were arrested in

1302
01:15:17.696 --> 01:15:21.626
mitosis had a dramatic downregulation of MCL1 levels.

1303
01:15:21.946 --> 01:15:25.666
This is a very short half-life protein, and so its levels are

1304
01:15:25.696 --> 01:15:29.196
regulated largely by active transcription of additional

1305
01:15:29.776 --> 01:15:33.376
mRNAs. And so as soon as cells paused in

1306
01:15:33.396 --> 01:15:37.216
mitosis essentially are unable to keep up the levels of MCL1, and it

1307
01:15:37.276 --> 01:15:41.176
drops quite dramatically. When we look at the actual interactions

1308
01:15:41.236 --> 01:15:44.976
between these proteins during the course of treatment, we see that normally

1309
01:15:45.036 --> 01:15:48.996
BCL-XL is actively sequestering Bim, Bak, and Bax in untreated

1310
01:15:49.036 --> 01:15:52.796
cells, keeping those proapoptotic molecules from inducing apoptosis.

1311
01:15:53.356 --> 01:15:56.756
When we give the degrader, we essentially are able to free those

1312
01:15:56.856 --> 01:16:00.076
proapoptotic proteins, and then in combination with the

1313
01:16:00.096 --> 01:16:03.996
paclitaxel, which then frees the proteins from the MCL1 that's

1314
01:16:04.056 --> 01:16:07.776
normally there to buffer against cell death, and then we get full-on

1315
01:16:08.176 --> 01:16:12.076
induction of apoptosis. And we can see that the converse is true

1316
01:16:12.116 --> 01:16:15.936
when we immunoprecipitate MCL1 and look for the reciprocal binding

1317
01:16:15.976 --> 01:16:16.676
interactions.

1318
01:16:18.996 --> 01:16:22.636
So now we wanted to test whether this was actually going to be effective in vivo.

1319
01:16:22.676 --> 01:16:26.636
So we utilized several different cell line and patient-derived

1320
01:16:26.696 --> 01:16:30.396
xenograft models. I'll show you the data from probably one of the most exciting

1321
01:16:30.476 --> 01:16:34.326
ones, which is DF83. This is a PDX model developed

1322
01:16:34.396 --> 01:16:38.176
at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute by Joyce Liu from a patient that

1323
01:16:38.236 --> 01:16:40.436
had four prior lines of chemotherapy treatment.

1324
01:16:41.476 --> 01:16:45.256
P53 mutant is known very well as a chemo-resistant

1325
01:16:45.336 --> 01:16:46.536
model of ovarian cancer.

1326
01:16:47.576 --> 01:16:51.536
At first, when we just utilized flank xenograft models for this,

1327
01:16:51.616 --> 01:16:55.436
we saw that true to form, these cells were very resistant

1328
01:16:55.736 --> 01:16:59.336
to paclitaxel treatment, also very resistant to the single agent

1329
01:16:59.436 --> 01:17:03.416
DT 2216 treatment. However, the combination therapy was able

1330
01:17:03.456 --> 01:17:07.015
to completely eradicate these tumors, and there was no evidence of tumor

1331
01:17:07.116 --> 01:17:09.116
regrowth even after cessation of therapy.

1332
01:17:10.116 --> 01:17:13.656
Interestingly, those that were treated with the DT 2216 showed evidence of

1333
01:17:13.716 --> 01:17:17.656
upregulation of MCL1 and BCL2 to drive this resistance

1334
01:17:17.776 --> 01:17:20.776
to the single-agent treatment, as we had expected based on that apoptotic

1335
01:17:20.816 --> 01:17:24.656
adaptation. We saw that there was a transient drop in

1336
01:17:24.676 --> 01:17:28.216
platelet levels in animals dosed with DT 2216,

1337
01:17:28.556 --> 01:17:32.156
consistent with the fact that it has the ABT-263 drug

1338
01:17:32.236 --> 01:17:36.196
as part of its core. But then as we are taking advantage of

1339
01:17:36.236 --> 01:17:39.636
this PROTAC-based activity, we see that the platelet levels were

1340
01:17:39.676 --> 01:17:42.636
maintained in safe levels for the duration of the experiment.

1341
01:17:43.296 --> 01:17:47.076
We didn't see any effects on white blood cell counts nor any

1342
01:17:47.156 --> 01:17:48.236
other toxicities.

1343
01:17:49.456 --> 01:17:53.436
This of course, led to a massive, very impressive increase in

1344
01:17:53.576 --> 01:17:54.436
overall survival.

1345
01:17:55.516 --> 01:17:58.976
When we looked in a separate cohort of mice and looked for evidence of

1346
01:17:59.056 --> 01:17:59.616
changes

1347
01:18:00.656 --> 01:18:04.556
in immunofluorescent staining of these tumor sections, we saw that

1348
01:18:04.576 --> 01:18:08.336
paclitaxel led to actually somewhat of an increase in BCL-XL

1349
01:18:08.396 --> 01:18:11.316
expression in these DF83 tumors.

1350
01:18:11.956 --> 01:18:15.526
Interestingly, some of the BCL-XLs seem to be actually even in the

1351
01:18:15.596 --> 01:18:19.476
nucleus. In the presence of the DT 2216, though, here in

1352
01:18:19.496 --> 01:18:21.126
green, we saw that there was a very

1353
01:18:22.836 --> 01:18:26.176
satisfying decrease in BCL-XL

1354
01:18:26.216 --> 01:18:30.156
expression in these tumors, regardless of whether paclitaxel was on board or not.

1355
01:18:31.396 --> 01:18:33.896
We also utilized an orthotopic model or

1356
01:18:34.736 --> 01:18:38.696
intraperitoneal model

1357
01:18:38.816 --> 01:18:42.796
where this is more mimicking the activity and the growth

1358
01:18:42.856 --> 01:18:46.736
of ovarian cancer in vivo, which frequently grows as ascites in the abdomen of

1359
01:18:46.776 --> 01:18:50.446
patients. And we saw that when we combined the paclitaxel and

1360
01:18:50.476 --> 01:18:54.196
DT 2216 treatment in this model, we saw that there was a very

1361
01:18:54.216 --> 01:18:57.956
impressive reduction in tumor burden getting down to just the background

1362
01:18:58.016 --> 01:19:01.316
level of luminescence that the assay would allow.

1363
01:19:01.936 --> 01:19:05.256
And there was a very nice extension of overall survival.

1364
01:19:05.276 --> 01:19:08.576
This was again tolerated very well with the platelet levels remaining quite

1365
01:19:08.616 --> 01:19:12.566
high.We didn't see any evidence of toxicities

1366
01:19:12.606 --> 01:19:15.946
in any of the tissues that we looked at, including the spleen, the lung, liver,

1367
01:19:16.046 --> 01:19:19.166
kidney, and heart, which was consistent with the very good

1368
01:19:19.646 --> 01:19:20.866
tolerability by the mice.

1369
01:19:21.966 --> 01:19:25.766
So this has led us to launch a clinical trial at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute,

1370
01:19:26.165 --> 01:19:29.666
testing the activity of DT 2216 in combination with

1371
01:19:29.686 --> 01:19:33.106
paclitaxel in platinum-resistant ovarian cancer in

1372
01:19:33.146 --> 01:19:36.386
collaboration with our clinical collaborator, Elizabeth Stover.

1373
01:19:36.826 --> 01:19:40.366
We're very excited about this. We have dosed, thus far, three patients,

1374
01:19:40.926 --> 01:19:44.666
and are excited to share data and updates with you in the coming several

1375
01:19:44.726 --> 01:19:45.066
months.

1376
01:19:47.426 --> 01:19:51.406
I want to highlight one thing, though, which is the applicability of some of

1377
01:19:51.446 --> 01:19:53.546
these findings across other cancers.

1378
01:19:53.586 --> 01:19:57.486
As part of this study, Xing Pang, who is a post-doc in the lab, has

1379
01:19:57.506 --> 01:20:01.046
been championing a lot of this work himself.

1380
01:20:01.546 --> 01:20:05.426
He tested the sensitivity of about 150 different cancer

1381
01:20:05.566 --> 01:20:09.126
cell lines to different types of BH3 mimetics, targeting BCL-XL,

1382
01:20:09.226 --> 01:20:12.366
BCL-2, or MCL-1 in order to gauge or

1383
01:20:12.646 --> 01:20:15.666
essentially characterize whether different cancer types would have

1384
01:20:16.546 --> 01:20:20.416
these types of dependencies. And in heme malignancies, shown here as

1385
01:20:20.446 --> 01:20:23.156
DLBCL and myeloma, we see what

1386
01:20:23.986 --> 01:20:24.256
we would

1387
01:20:25.386 --> 01:20:28.966
assume or think based on the literature, which is that there are some dependencies

1388
01:20:28.986 --> 01:20:32.506
on MCL-1, for example, in multiple myeloma, and in

1389
01:20:32.586 --> 01:20:34.726
AML, we see some dependence on BCL-2.

1390
01:20:35.166 --> 01:20:38.646
However, in solid cancers, there's only mild dependencies, and they're

1391
01:20:38.686 --> 01:20:42.266
really restricted, for the most part, to BCL-XL.

1392
01:20:42.946 --> 01:20:46.406
But what was interesting as part of this is he also did combination treatments of

1393
01:20:46.486 --> 01:20:50.146
all these mimetics together. And what was quite dramatic is that there was

1394
01:20:50.286 --> 01:20:54.046
no cancer cell line or very, very few that could withstand

1395
01:20:54.106 --> 01:20:57.766
combination treatment with BCL-XL plus MCL-1 inhibition.

1396
01:20:58.116 --> 01:21:02.056
This was effective even in the toughest to treat glioblastoma cell lines, as

1397
01:21:02.086 --> 01:21:02.685
shown here.

1398
01:21:04.266 --> 01:21:08.186
This is not clinically that relevant because of the fact that we

1399
01:21:08.266 --> 01:21:11.526
can't target BCL-XL and MCL-1 at the same time,

1400
01:21:12.086 --> 01:21:16.066
especially with BH3 mimetics. In other studies done by Johan Spets in my lab a

1401
01:21:16.106 --> 01:21:19.985
few years ago, he showed that when we dose animals with BCL-XL plus

1402
01:21:20.066 --> 01:21:23.866
MCL-1 inhibitors, we actually see a very strong toxicity in the

1403
01:21:23.906 --> 01:21:27.546
vasculature, which then leads to the mice succumbing to this

1404
01:21:27.586 --> 01:21:28.886
treatment pretty rapidly.

1405
01:21:29.766 --> 01:21:33.266
And this happens really in combination with the BCL-XL and

1406
01:21:33.346 --> 01:21:34.886
MCL-1 inhibitor together.

1407
01:21:35.706 --> 01:21:36.146
So really,

1408
01:21:37.206 --> 01:21:41.086
what this tells us is that we're really getting excellent synergy from the

1409
01:21:41.146 --> 01:21:45.086
targeting of MCL-1 plus BCL-XL in these ovarian cancer cells, but the

1410
01:21:45.166 --> 01:21:47.286
MCL-1 targeting has to be indirect.

1411
01:21:47.615 --> 01:21:51.196
And as we see here, when we ran a panel of different chemotherapeutic agents

1412
01:21:51.546 --> 01:21:55.365
and their effect on MCL-1 levels in ovarian cancer cells, we see

1413
01:21:55.406 --> 01:21:59.026
really that only paclitaxel was able to deplete MCL-1 levels.

1414
01:21:59.366 --> 01:22:02.426
And so we believe that is what's giving us this really excellent

1415
01:22:02.886 --> 01:22:05.886
synergistic cell death in combination with the BCL-XL

1416
01:22:05.906 --> 01:22:09.666
degrader. And just to also highlight the

1417
01:22:09.726 --> 01:22:13.046
fact that this is not restricted to ovarian cancer, we see that when we

1418
01:22:14.046 --> 01:22:17.426
test the sensitivity of DT 2216 plus paclitaxel

1419
01:22:17.786 --> 01:22:21.506
across a range of solid cancer cell types, both P53 mutant and

1420
01:22:21.586 --> 01:22:25.305
wild type, we see excellent evidence of synergy across these.

1421
01:22:26.266 --> 01:22:29.696
And finally, interestingly, we see that this is not just

1422
01:22:29.706 --> 01:22:33.386
restricted to paclitaxel or microtubule targeting agents.

1423
01:22:33.406 --> 01:22:37.366
We see that any agent that is able to induce mitotic arrest synergizes very

1424
01:22:37.466 --> 01:22:41.086
well with BCL-XL degradation. So we think that this is also an

1425
01:22:41.126 --> 01:22:43.086
exciting avenue for potentially targeting,

1426
01:22:44.146 --> 01:22:48.046
or enhancing the activity of aurora kinase inhibitors and polo kinase inhibitors.

1427
01:22:48.776 --> 01:22:52.746
And in fact, when we look at combination therapies with BCL-XL

1428
01:22:52.786 --> 01:22:56.506
inhibition in solid cancers, including breast cancer, colon, and pancreas,

1429
01:22:56.946 --> 01:23:00.626
we see that mitosis-targeting agents are by far the most effective and give you

1430
01:23:00.666 --> 01:23:03.286
the highest percentages of synergy.

1431
01:23:03.806 --> 01:23:07.426
That being said, there are other agents that also would combine well with BCL-XL

1432
01:23:07.446 --> 01:23:10.486
inhibition, and we feel like this is going to be an exciting avenue going forward.

1433
01:23:11.406 --> 01:23:15.046
So just to give you a quick one-line summary, really targeting

1434
01:23:15.106 --> 01:23:18.786
BCL-XL synergizes with agents that trigger mitotic arrest, including

1435
01:23:18.826 --> 01:23:22.146
microtubule targeting drugs or kinase inhibitors, polo kinase inhibitors.

1436
01:23:22.606 --> 01:23:26.566
We think that this could be widely utilized to enhance therapy

1437
01:23:26.626 --> 01:23:29.726
outcomes for patients with ovarian cancer and other solid tumors.

1438
01:23:30.426 --> 01:23:33.686
With that, I just want to thank the people in my lab that did this work and our

1439
01:23:33.695 --> 01:23:37.646
excellent collaborators, especially Elizabeth Stover, who's been championing the

1440
01:23:38.726 --> 01:23:41.666
patient clinical trial data and clinical trial

1441
01:23:42.926 --> 01:23:46.846
execution so well. And I just want to also highlight Xing Pang,

1442
01:23:46.906 --> 01:23:50.586
who has done the lion's share of this work. Thank you so much for your time.

1443
01:24:06.006 --> 01:24:08.386
Absolutely stunning work. Congratulations.

1444
01:24:09.166 --> 01:24:10.186
The combination with

1445
01:24:11.546 --> 01:24:14.146
mitotic drugs like PLK1,

1446
01:24:15.146 --> 01:24:18.966
PLK4, aurora kinases, may have a different mechanism.

1447
01:24:19.046 --> 01:24:22.896
So what we see is induction of polyploidization and followed

1448
01:24:22.926 --> 01:24:26.806
by mitotic catastrophe. So I think the cells cannot maintain

1449
01:24:27.606 --> 01:24:29.366
growth at these high ploidy levels.

1450
01:24:29.746 --> 01:24:33.306
And then, of course, if you also push them into

1451
01:24:33.346 --> 01:24:35.306
apoptosis, they will become very sensitive.

1452
01:24:35.646 --> 01:24:38.286
But that would be a mechanism to consider when you combine,

1453
01:24:39.246 --> 01:24:42.946
let's say, PLK1 inhibitors and BCL-XL

1454
01:24:43.006 --> 01:24:43.586
degraders.

1455
01:24:44.406 --> 01:24:48.326
Yeah, I think it's an excellent point, and I didn't talk about it here,

1456
01:24:48.466 --> 01:24:50.486
but one of the other mechanisms that,

1457
01:24:51.446 --> 01:24:55.126
speaking of your aneuploidy, another thing that we see happening is the

1458
01:24:55.166 --> 01:24:59.046
acquisition of a senescent state in cells in response to paclitaxel, and I

1459
01:24:59.066 --> 01:25:02.686
think that also happens with aurora kinase inhibitors and polo kinase inhibitors.

1460
01:25:02.966 --> 01:25:06.546
So we see that those cells are profoundly sensitive to BCL-XL

1461
01:25:06.566 --> 01:25:10.406
inhibition as well. And so we think that there's multiple cell states

1462
01:25:10.446 --> 01:25:13.946
being induced by these therapies that then can be

1463
01:25:14.426 --> 01:25:17.866
exploited by the BCL-XL inhibition to drive potent cell death.

1464
01:25:18.266 --> 01:25:19.366
But it's an excellent point.

1465
01:25:19.886 --> 01:25:21.926
So BCL-XL induces senescence,

1466
01:25:22.766 --> 01:25:26.166
of course. But what I learned from another institution is that

1467
01:25:26.458 --> 01:25:30.238
Polyploidization may be a very good target for

1468
01:25:30.418 --> 01:25:33.458
particular MP53 mutant leukemias.

1469
01:25:33.538 --> 01:25:37.018
So we have PLK4 inhibition, and we have high

1470
01:25:37.038 --> 01:25:40.018
sensitivity of P53 mutant leukemias in that case.

1471
01:25:41.858 --> 01:25:45.158
So that's something to consider for P53 mutant ones. Mm-hmm.

1472
01:25:45.378 --> 01:25:48.878
Absolutely. And in our studies, we've seen that P53 mutant

1473
01:25:49.558 --> 01:25:53.298
cell lines certainly are just as sensitive, and in certain cases even more

1474
01:25:53.358 --> 01:25:57.198
sensitive than P53 wild type cells to these agents.

1475
01:26:00.538 --> 01:26:03.258
I was just wondering if you've tried the DT

1476
01:26:03.538 --> 01:26:06.958
2261 in combination with carboplatin

1477
01:26:08.018 --> 01:26:11.918
or triple combination, and also its PARP inhibitors, and

1478
01:26:12.258 --> 01:26:13.098
how those compare.

1479
01:26:13.798 --> 01:26:17.358
Yeah, that's a great point. So, a reviewer of this paper asked us that same

1480
01:26:17.458 --> 01:26:19.158
question, so maybe that was you, I don't know.

1481
01:26:19.478 --> 01:26:19.618
But

1482
01:26:20.798 --> 01:26:24.738
it's actually kind of interesting because we thought in all the studies that we had

1483
01:26:24.778 --> 01:26:28.558
done, we saw this molecular mechanism driving the synergy

1484
01:26:28.578 --> 01:26:32.218
between the paclitaxel and the BCL-XL degrader.

1485
01:26:33.018 --> 01:26:36.498
And so we definitely went in that direction because of that

1486
01:26:37.298 --> 01:26:40.778
synergy. But we went back and did those same exact experiments with

1487
01:26:40.818 --> 01:26:44.678
carboplatin, and we see, although there's not as much synergy with carboplatin

1488
01:26:44.738 --> 01:26:48.648
plus a BCL-XL degrader, there was definitely still evidence of synergy.

1489
01:26:48.678 --> 01:26:52.418
And quite interestingly, when we did the triple combination, what's

1490
01:26:52.438 --> 01:26:56.418
known to the ovarian cancer field is that actually paclitaxel and carboplatin have

1491
01:26:56.458 --> 01:27:00.158
some antagonism because of the fact that carboplatin can drive cell

1492
01:27:00.218 --> 01:27:03.678
cycle arrest and reduces the sensitivity of cells to

1493
01:27:03.718 --> 01:27:07.638
paclitaxel. And so we see that, this antagonism between those agents.

1494
01:27:07.978 --> 01:27:11.778
And when we have DT 2216 on board, it's actually able to

1495
01:27:11.818 --> 01:27:15.718
enhance that sensitivity. So in the long term, we feel like

1496
01:27:15.778 --> 01:27:19.188
the best avenue forward would be to get this into frontline

1497
01:27:19.418 --> 01:27:22.968
treatment with carboplatin and paclitaxel if

1498
01:27:22.998 --> 01:27:26.338
possible. But we're taking it one step at a time, so we have to do the

1499
01:27:26.598 --> 01:27:30.078
paclitaxel treatments first. But yeah, great question, something that we're really

1500
01:27:30.118 --> 01:27:30.558
interested in.

1501
01:27:31.098 --> 01:27:33.088
Great, and then also PARP inhibitors. Sorry, that was last.

1502
01:27:33.118 --> 01:27:35.518
Oh, yeah. That was your other question. Thanks.

1503
01:27:36.518 --> 01:27:39.998
Yeah, so that was one of the first things that we looked at, was PARP

1504
01:27:40.038 --> 01:27:43.798
inhibition and BCL-XL degradation simply because we

1505
01:27:43.818 --> 01:27:47.668
thought that there's some signals for toxicities with paclitaxel and

1506
01:27:47.678 --> 01:27:51.578
carboplatin to try to avoid. And we did not see a very high

1507
01:27:51.638 --> 01:27:55.058
level of synergy with PARP inhibitors and BCL-XL degraders.

1508
01:27:55.618 --> 01:27:59.438
That being said, we only tested a few models, and so I feel like

1509
01:27:59.498 --> 01:28:03.308
there is an opportunity to go back and look a little more deeply at that to see if

1510
01:28:03.358 --> 01:28:05.658
we potentially missed something.

1511
01:28:05.738 --> 01:28:06.118
Thank you.

1512
01:28:06.318 --> 01:28:08.008
Great question.

1513
01:28:08.008 --> 01:28:10.578
Hi. Masha Porovski, PMV Pharma.

1514
01:28:11.578 --> 01:28:15.218
It's really heartening to see potential paths for these in solid tumors for

1515
01:28:15.438 --> 01:28:18.958
targeting these pathways. But I'm wondering if

1516
01:28:19.378 --> 01:28:23.018
the changing landscape in ovarian cancer is influencing

1517
01:28:23.138 --> 01:28:26.638
how you're viewing these combinations and the

1518
01:28:26.658 --> 01:28:29.898
emergence and moving into frontline of

1519
01:28:29.998 --> 01:28:30.698
ADCs,

1520
01:28:31.518 --> 01:28:35.318
whether or not there's a path there for the

1521
01:28:35.338 --> 01:28:36.418
BCL-XL

1522
01:28:37.398 --> 01:28:37.958
inhibition.

1523
01:28:38.498 --> 01:28:42.028
Yeah, it's such a great point. And it's interesting that

1524
01:28:42.058 --> 01:28:46.028
carboplatin and paclitaxel really have been mainstays of ovarian cancer therapy

1525
01:28:46.058 --> 01:28:49.958
for decades. Very little movement therapeutically, but more recently there have

1526
01:28:49.998 --> 01:28:53.398
been some exciting approvals and some movement on

1527
01:28:53.458 --> 01:28:57.038
that. We are thinking about that. We know

1528
01:28:57.078 --> 01:29:00.768
that at least the way that we had set it up, we wanted to first look at

1529
01:29:00.818 --> 01:29:04.438
this, again, this synergistic induction of cell death with the paclitaxel

1530
01:29:04.458 --> 01:29:07.958
plus DT 2216, and we know that the weekly

1531
01:29:07.998 --> 01:29:11.698
paclitaxel is a second-line or third-line treatment for these

1532
01:29:11.718 --> 01:29:14.318
patients. So we're starting out there.

1533
01:29:14.378 --> 01:29:17.778
But certainly if we can make some progress there, then we imagine that this would

1534
01:29:17.798 --> 01:29:21.278
actually combine very well with some of these ADCs, where the

1535
01:29:21.318 --> 01:29:25.178
payload frequently is a microtubule targeting agent as well.

1536
01:29:25.187 --> 01:29:28.858
And so we feel like it's going to lead to that depletion of MCL-1 and potentially a

1537
01:29:28.928 --> 01:29:31.918
synergistic cell death. So it is something we're thinking about a lot.

1538
01:29:32.038 --> 01:29:32.758
That's a good point.

1539
01:29:35.598 --> 01:29:37.458
Excellent work, Chris. Fantastic.

1540
01:29:38.478 --> 01:29:42.358
It was only possible because you had the BCL-XL inhibitor

1541
01:29:42.398 --> 01:29:46.267
hooked up to be degraded by VHL. Now, couldn't you do the

1542
01:29:46.398 --> 01:29:49.758
same with the MCL-1 inhibitor and thereby also gain

1543
01:29:50.238 --> 01:29:53.978
independence of the toxicity that you claim that that's why you

1544
01:29:54.038 --> 01:29:57.738
cannot combine it with the MCL-1 inhibition directly?

1545
01:29:59.278 --> 01:30:03.138
So that's a great point. However, the

1546
01:30:03.218 --> 01:30:07.178
issue with the combination of the BCL-XL plus MCL-1

1547
01:30:07.378 --> 01:30:09.558
inhibition is really in the vasculature.

1548
01:30:09.718 --> 01:30:13.658
And so you would need to have some kind of degrader that didn't degrade BCL-XL in

1549
01:30:13.678 --> 01:30:17.498
the vasculature. We do think that BCL-XL is getting degraded in the vasculature.

1550
01:30:17.658 --> 01:30:17.778
Mm-hmm.

1551
01:30:17.808 --> 01:30:21.678
It's just that it's not dying the same way when you combine the

1552
01:30:21.718 --> 01:30:25.498
direct inhibitor because of the fact that paclitaxel only targets

1553
01:30:25.558 --> 01:30:29.438
cycling cells, and so that MCL-1 downregulation isn't happening in the

1554
01:30:29.458 --> 01:30:31.858
vasculature, which is non-cycling. It's mostly quiescent.

1555
01:30:31.898 --> 01:30:34.718
There's some degree of proliferation, but it's very small.

1556
01:30:35.138 --> 01:30:37.978
So we think that's where the therapeutic index really comes from.

1557
01:30:38.378 --> 01:30:42.078
Now, can we design an MCL-1 degrader that would allow us to

1558
01:30:42.118 --> 01:30:45.858
avoid the cardiotoxicity that we've been talking about here today?

1559
01:30:46.178 --> 01:30:47.658
I think there are interesting opportunities.

1560
01:30:47.678 --> 01:30:51.378
In fact, someone told me before the session that they have developed a

1561
01:30:51.638 --> 01:30:54.998
degrader for MCL-1 that might be sparing the

1562
01:30:55.378 --> 01:30:59.038
cardiomyocytes to some extent. So I think that that is really an

1563
01:30:59.058 --> 01:31:02.778
interesting avenue to go down. And I think this degradation, I

1564
01:31:03.198 --> 01:31:06.258
didn't have a chance to really talk about it, but you can see it in the manuscript.

1565
01:31:06.538 --> 01:31:10.398
There's also inherent advantages to degrading pro-survival

1566
01:31:10.458 --> 01:31:14.438
proteins over just simple inhibition, and that's because of the fact

1567
01:31:14.478 --> 01:31:18.118
that you're able to first of all get rid of nearly

1568
01:31:18.138 --> 01:31:19.918
100% of the protein.

1569
01:31:19.988 --> 01:31:20.008
You go deeper.

1570
01:31:20.008 --> 01:31:22.818
There's less opportunity. Yeah, there's a deeper response.

1571
01:31:22.838 --> 01:31:25.798
There's less opportunities for the cells to rapidly adapt.

1572
01:31:25.838 --> 01:31:29.458
And so we see that there's faster acquisition of resistance when we

1573
01:31:29.518 --> 01:31:32.078
do a conventional inhibitor versus a degrader.

1574
01:31:32.758 --> 01:31:36.378
And so we think that potentially down the road, this would be the most effective

1575
01:31:36.418 --> 01:31:40.298
way forward for some of these other proteins, including MCL-1, if we can get there.

1576
01:31:40.758 --> 01:31:44.638
So for the MCL-1 degrader, you would need to have an E3 ligase that

1577
01:31:44.958 --> 01:31:48.108
works in the ovarian cancer cells but does not work in the endothelium.

1578
01:31:48.798 --> 01:31:49.108
Right?

1579
01:31:49.108 --> 01:31:49.718
And does not work-

1580
01:31:49.798 --> 01:31:50.438
And in the cardio

1581
01:31:50.698 --> 01:31:52.338
... in the cardiomyocytes, ideally.

1582
01:31:52.418 --> 01:31:52.808
Yeah, exactly.

1583
01:31:52.808 --> 01:31:54.488
Yeah. That's exactly right. If you know of one,

1584
01:31:55.378 --> 01:31:56.158
we can talk after.

1585
01:31:57.418 --> 01:31:58.378
If I could comment

1586
01:31:59.218 --> 01:32:02.998
on the inhibitors, which are cardiotoxic or not, they do

1587
01:32:03.098 --> 01:32:06.958
cause accumulation of MCL-1 for the reasons that you mentioned,

1588
01:32:07.018 --> 01:32:08.918
through the decreased degradation.

1589
01:32:09.018 --> 01:32:12.338
So we at least see up to eightfold increased levels of

1590
01:32:12.438 --> 01:32:16.118
MCL-1 after inhibitors in cardiomyocytes and other cell

1591
01:32:16.178 --> 01:32:19.858
types. So this can be also big differentiating

1592
01:32:19.958 --> 01:32:23.898
factor versus, let's say, degraders that can cleanly remove

1593
01:32:23.958 --> 01:32:24.918
this protein.

1594
01:32:25.078 --> 01:32:28.178
Oh, right. Yeah. Absolutely. And yeah, so that is

1595
01:32:28.248 --> 01:32:32.158
one of the other things that we saw consistently was that

1596
01:32:32.198 --> 01:32:36.077
when we inhibit BCL-XL, BCL-XL itself is going

1597
01:32:36.158 --> 01:32:40.058
up in expression. It's getting stabilized, it's accumulating

1598
01:32:40.118 --> 01:32:43.438
because you're constantly feeding more BCL-XL mRNAs into the process.

1599
01:32:43.478 --> 01:32:45.918
If you're degrading it, you at least take away that one crutch.

1600
01:32:46.678 --> 01:32:48.638
And so we think that that's going to be better long term.

1601
01:32:50.578 --> 01:32:50.798
Great.

